{"title_page": "Street Child World Cup", "text_new": "{{advert|date=March 2016}}\nThe '''Street Child World Cup''' is a global movement for street children to receive the protection and opportunities that all children are entitled to. Ahead of each [[FIFA World Cup]], they unite street children from across five continents to play football and unite in a unique international conference. Together through football, art and campaigning their aim is to challenge the negative perceptions and treatment of street children around the world.\n\n==History==\nThe first Street Child World Cup was held in [[Durban]], [[South Africa]], in March 2010<ref>{{cite news|last=Fihlani |first=Pumza |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/8567522.stm |title=Street children aim for World Cup victory |publisher=BBC News |date=2010-03-15 |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Family |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/family/7251550/Simon-Mayo-Soul-music-and-the-Street-Child-World-Cup.html |title=Simon Mayo: Soul music and the Street Child World Cup |publisher=Telegraph |date= 2010-02-19|accessdate=2012-05-22 |location=London}}</ref> The event brought together teams of [[street children]] and former street children from Brazil, South Africa, Nicaragua, Ukraine, India, the Philippines and Tanzania. The participants were between 14 and 16 years old at the time of the event and all had experience of living full-time on the streets without family. Each squad of 9 players included 3 girls. A representative team of young people from Manchester, UK, also took part in the tournament.  This team was mentored by UK children's TV presenter [[Andy Akinwolere]], and his journey was covered on the BBC Children's TV show, [[Blue Peter]].\n\nThe Street Child World Cup was initiated by UK human rights charity the [[Amos Trust]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amostrust.org/ |title=amos trust |publisher=amos trust |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref>  It was hosted in Durban by [[Umthombo Street Children]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Lawrence Jones Design, US-UK, larryljonesdesign.com |url=http://www.umthombo.org/ |title=Umthombo Street Children - the Voice from the Streets |publisher=Umthombo.org |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> and the [[Durban University of Technology]].\n\nEach team was brought by a street child organisation based in the contributing country:\nAction for Brazil's Children;\n[[Casa Alianza|Casa Alianza Nicaragua]];\nDepaul Kharkiv (Ukraine);\nYouth Football Club [[Rurka Kalan]] and the Khalsa Football Academy (India);\nCaretakers of the Environment Tanzania, through [[Tanzania Street Children Sports Academy]] (TSC Sports Academy) \nA network of charities worked together to bring a team from the Philippines.\nThe UK team was brought by the M13 Youth Project.\n\nBetween 12 and 22 March 2010, the participating children competed in a 7-a-side football tournament, created artworks which were subsequently exhibited in the Durban Art Gallery and at the [[Foundling Museum]], London,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foundlingmuseum.org.uk/PastExhibitions.php |title=Events |publisher=Foundling Museum |date=2012-05-11 |access-date=2012-05-22 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720053653/http://www.foundlingmuseum.org.uk/PastExhibitions.php |archive-date=2011-07-20 |df= }}</ref> and took part in a youth participation conference.  The outcomes of the conference were published in November 2010 as 'The Durban Declaration'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crin.org/violence/search/closeup.asp?infoid=23590 |title=Violence Study - STREET CHILDREN: The Durban Declaration - a call to action from the Street Child World Cup |publisher=CRIN |date=2010-11-25 |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> This emphasises street children's right to be heard, right to a home, right to protection from violence, and right to access health and education.  Girls participating in the Street Child World Cup produced a Street Girl's Manifesto which was published as part of [[Plan International|Plan International's]] 2010 [[Because I Am a Girl (campaign)|'Because I am a Girl']] report on the state of the world's girls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://plan-international.org/girls/resources/digital-and-urban-frontiers-2010.php |title=Because I am a Girl: Digital and Urban Frontiers 2010 - Because I am a Girl - Plan |publisher=Plan-international.org |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref>\n\nThe artwork created at the event was facilitated by Momentum Arts, a Cambridge-based arts inclusion charity.  Specialised coaching was provided by Coaching for Hope.\n\nThe main overall sponsors of the event were [[Deloitte]], and the event was known as the Deloitte Street Child World Cup.\n\nThe football tournament was won by India,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8579974.stm |title=India win Street Child World Cup in South Africa |publisher=BBC News |date=2010-03-22 |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> who beat [[Tanzania Street Children Sports Academy|Tanzania]] in the finals.  The Shield was won by the Philippines team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.inquirer.net/amateur/amateur/view/20100329-261381/RP-miracle-in-world-football-tilt |title=RP \u2018miracle\u2019 in world football tilt - INQUIRER.net, Philippine News for Filipinos |publisher=Sports.inquirer.net |date=2010-03-29 |access-date=2012-05-22 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612143447/http://sports.inquirer.net/amateur/amateur/view/20100329-261381/RP-miracle-in-world-football-tilt |archive-date=2012-06-12 |df= }}</ref>  Ukraine won the Fair Play award.\n\nThe Philippine team will be managed by the [[Fairplay For All Foundation]].\n\nOn March 27, 2014, a 10-day tournament and conference will kick off in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. David Beckham: \u201cI look forward to Brazil in 2014 when street children from around the world will play football and represent the millions of children who still live or work on our streets.\u201c  At least 16 countries will take part represented by street child organisations committed to the rights of street children. This list so far includes Brazil, Argentina, Columbia, USA, Ukraine, Indonesia, India, [[Pakistan]], Philippines, Burundi, South Africa, Sierre Leone, Kenya, [[Tanzania Street Children Sports Academy|Tanzania]], Egypt and Mauritius.\n\n01 march 2019 Bangladeshi street children was also participated in the first street child cricket world cup tournament. The children were from LEEDO fund. \n\n==Participating Nations==\n\nBelow is a list of all the participating nations in all editions.\n{|\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*{{flagIOC2|ARG|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|BRA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|BDI|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|EGY|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|GBR|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|ESA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|INA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|IND|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|KEN|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|LBR|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|MRI|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|MOZ|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|PHI|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|TAN|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|RSA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|NCA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|PAK|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|USA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|ZIM|Street Child World Cup|}}\n|}\n\n==Results==\nUntil the 2014 edition, teams were composed of both boys and girls. Starting on the [[2014 Street Child World Cup]] edition, there was a separate tournament for boys and girls.\n\n===Boys===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%\"\n|-\n!width=5%|Year\n!width=10%|Host\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=14%|Winners\n!width=10%|Score\n!width=14%|Runners-up\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=14%|Third place\n!width=10%|Score\n!width=14%|Fourth place\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=4%|Number of teams\n|-\n|[[2014 Street Child World Cup|2014]]\n|{{flag|Brazil}}\n|{{flagicon|Tanzania|size=30px}} <br/> Tanzania\n|4-1<br />\n|{{flagicon|Burundi|size=30px}} <br/> [[Burundi]]\n|{{flagicon|Pakistan|size=30px}} <br/> [[Pakistan]]\n|'''1\u20131''' <br/> (3\u20132[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|p]])\n|{{flagicon|United States|size=30px}} <br/> [[United States]]\n|15\n|- \n|}\n\n===Girls===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%\"\n|-\n!width=5%|Year\n!width=10%|Host\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=14%|Winners \n!width=10%|Score\n!width=14%|Runners-up\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=14%|Third place\n!width=10%|Score\n!width=14%|Fourth place\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=4%|Number of teams\n|-\n|[[2014 Street Child World Cup|2014]]\n|{{flag|Brazil}}\n|{{flagicon|Brazil|size=30px}} <br/> [[Brazil]]\n|'''1\u20130'''\n|{{flagicon|Philippines|size=30px}} <br/> [[Philippines]]\n|{{flagicon|El Salvador|size=30px}} <br/> [[El Salvador]]\n|'''1\u20131''' <br/> (2\u20131[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|p]])\n|{{flagicon|Mozambique|size=30px}} <br/> [[Mozambique]]\n|9\n|- \n|}\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://streetchildworldcup.org/\n* http://www.amostrust.org/\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141108212132/http://tscacademy.org/ Tanzania Street Children Sports Academy]\n\n{{homelessness}}\n\n[[Category:Youth association football competitions for international teams]]\n[[Category:Non-FIFA football competitions]]\n[[Category:Street children]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=March 2016}}\nThe '''Street Child World Cup''' is a global movement for street children to receive the protection and opportunities that all children are entitled to. Ahead of each [[FIFA World Cup]], they unite street children from across five continents to play football and unite in a unique international conference. Together through football, art and campaigning their aim is to challenge the negative perceptions and treatment of street children around the world.\n\n==History==\nThe first Street Child World Cup was held in [[Durban]], [[South Africa]], in March 2010<ref>{{cite news|last=Fihlani |first=Pumza |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/8567522.stm |title=Street children aim for World Cup victory |publisher=BBC News |date=2010-03-15 |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Family |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/family/7251550/Simon-Mayo-Soul-music-and-the-Street-Child-World-Cup.html |title=Simon Mayo: Soul music and the Street Child World Cup |publisher=Telegraph |date= 2010-02-19|accessdate=2012-05-22 |location=London}}</ref> The event brought together teams of [[street children]] and former street children from Brazil, South Africa, Nicaragua, Ukraine, India, the Philippines and Tanzania. The participants were between 14 and 16 years old at the time of the event and all had experience of living full-time on the streets without family. Each squad of 9 players included 3 girls. A representative team of young people from Manchester, UK, also took part in the tournament.  This team was mentored by UK children's TV presenter [[Andy Akinwolere]], and his journey was covered on the BBC Children's TV show, [[Blue Peter]].\n\nThe Street Child World Cup was initiated by UK human rights charity the [[Amos Trust]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amostrust.org/ |title=amos trust |publisher=amos trust |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref>  It was hosted in Durban by [[Umthombo Street Children]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Lawrence Jones Design, US-UK, larryljonesdesign.com |url=http://www.umthombo.org/ |title=Umthombo Street Children - the Voice from the Streets |publisher=Umthombo.org |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> and the [[Durban University of Technology]].\n\nEach team was brought by a street child organisation based in the contributing country:\nAction for Brazil's Children;\n[[Casa Alianza|Casa Alianza Nicaragua]];\nDepaul Kharkiv (Ukraine);\nYouth Football Club [[Rurka Kalan]] and the Khalsa Football Academy (India);\nCaretakers of the Environment Tanzania, through [[Tanzania Street Children Sports Academy]] (TSC Sports Academy) \nA network of charities worked together to bring a team from the Philippines.\nThe UK team was brought by the M13 Youth Project.\n\nBetween 12 and 22 March 2010, the participating children competed in a 7-a-side football tournament, created artworks which were subsequently exhibited in the Durban Art Gallery and at the [[Foundling Museum]], London,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foundlingmuseum.org.uk/PastExhibitions.php |title=Events |publisher=Foundling Museum |date=2012-05-11 |access-date=2012-05-22 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720053653/http://www.foundlingmuseum.org.uk/PastExhibitions.php |archive-date=2011-07-20 |df= }}</ref> and took part in a youth participation conference.  The outcomes of the conference were published in November 2010 as 'The Durban Declaration'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crin.org/violence/search/closeup.asp?infoid=23590 |title=Violence Study - STREET CHILDREN: The Durban Declaration - a call to action from the Street Child World Cup |publisher=CRIN |date=2010-11-25 |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> This emphasises street children's right to be heard, right to a home, right to protection from violence, and right to access health and education.  Girls participating in the Street Child World Cup produced a Street Girl's Manifesto which was published as part of [[Plan International|Plan International's]] 2010 [[Because I Am a Girl (campaign)|'Because I am a Girl']] report on the state of the world's girls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://plan-international.org/girls/resources/digital-and-urban-frontiers-2010.php |title=Because I am a Girl: Digital and Urban Frontiers 2010 - Because I am a Girl - Plan |publisher=Plan-international.org |date= |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref>\n\nThe artwork created at the event was facilitated by Momentum Arts, a Cambridge-based arts inclusion charity.  Specialised coaching was provided by Coaching for Hope.\n\nThe main overall sponsors of the event were [[Deloitte]], and the event was known as the Deloitte Street Child World Cup.\n\nThe football tournament was won by India,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8579974.stm |title=India win Street Child World Cup in South Africa |publisher=BBC News |date=2010-03-22 |accessdate=2012-05-22}}</ref> who beat [[Tanzania Street Children Sports Academy|Tanzania]] in the finals.  The Shield was won by the Philippines team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.inquirer.net/amateur/amateur/view/20100329-261381/RP-miracle-in-world-football-tilt |title=RP \u2018miracle\u2019 in world football tilt - INQUIRER.net, Philippine News for Filipinos |publisher=Sports.inquirer.net |date=2010-03-29 |access-date=2012-05-22 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612143447/http://sports.inquirer.net/amateur/amateur/view/20100329-261381/RP-miracle-in-world-football-tilt |archive-date=2012-06-12 |df= }}</ref>  Ukraine won the Fair Play award.\n\nThe Philippine team will be managed by the [[Fairplay For All Foundation]].\n\nOn March 27, 2014, a 10-day tournament and conference will kick off in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. David Beckham: \u201cI look forward to Brazil in 2014 when street children from around the world will play football and represent the millions of children who still live or work on our streets.\u201c  At least 16 countries will take part represented by street child organisations committed to the rights of street children. This list so far includes Brazil, Argentina, Columbia, USA, Ukraine, Indonesia, India, [[Pakistan]], Philippines, Burundi, South Africa, Sierre Leone, Kenya, [[Tanzania Street Children Sports Academy|Tanzania]], Egypt and Mauritius.\n\n==Participating Nations==\n\nBelow is a list of all the participating nations in all editions.\n{|\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*{{flagIOC2|ARG|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|BRA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|BDI|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|EGY|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|GBR|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|ESA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|INA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|IND|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|KEN|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|LBR|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|MRI|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|MOZ|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|PHI|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|TAN|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|RSA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|NCA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|PAK|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|USA|Street Child World Cup|}}\n*{{flagIOC2|ZIM|Street Child World Cup|}}\n|}\n\n==Results==\nUntil the 2014 edition, teams were composed of both boys and girls. Starting on the [[2014 Street Child World Cup]] edition, there was a separate tournament for boys and girls.\n\n===Boys===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%\"\n|-\n!width=5%|Year\n!width=10%|Host\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=14%|Winners\n!width=10%|Score\n!width=14%|Runners-up\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=14%|Third place\n!width=10%|Score\n!width=14%|Fourth place\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=4%|Number of teams\n|-\n|[[2014 Street Child World Cup|2014]]\n|{{flag|Brazil}}\n|{{flagicon|Tanzania|size=30px}} <br/> Tanzania\n|4-1<br />\n|{{flagicon|Burundi|size=30px}} <br/> [[Burundi]]\n|{{flagicon|Pakistan|size=30px}} <br/> [[Pakistan]]\n|'''1\u20131''' <br/> (3\u20132[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|p]])\n|{{flagicon|United States|size=30px}} <br/> [[United States]]\n|15\n|- \n|}\n\n===Girls===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width:100%\"\n|-\n!width=5%|Year\n!width=10%|Host\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=14%|Winners \n!width=10%|Score\n!width=14%|Runners-up\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=14%|Third place\n!width=10%|Score\n!width=14%|Fourth place\n!width=1% rowspan=20 bgcolor=ffffff|\n!width=4%|Number of teams\n|-\n|[[2014 Street Child World Cup|2014]]\n|{{flag|Brazil}}\n|{{flagicon|Brazil|size=30px}} <br/> [[Brazil]]\n|'''1\u20130'''\n|{{flagicon|Philippines|size=30px}} <br/> [[Philippines]]\n|{{flagicon|El Salvador|size=30px}} <br/> [[El Salvador]]\n|'''1\u20131''' <br/> (2\u20131[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|p]])\n|{{flagicon|Mozambique|size=30px}} <br/> [[Mozambique]]\n|9\n|- \n|}\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://streetchildworldcup.org/\n* http://www.amostrust.org/\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141108212132/http://tscacademy.org/ Tanzania Street Children Sports Academy]\n\n{{homelessness}}\n\n[[Category:Youth association football competitions for international teams]]\n[[Category:Non-FIFA football competitions]]\n[[Category:Street children]]\n", "name_user": "Tasnim jahan jerin0.0", "label": "safe", "comment": "In this page it is not written that Bangladesh has also participated. I wrote only 2 or 3 lines about the Bangladeshi participants .", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Street_Child_World_Cup"}
{"title_page": "Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis\n| synonyms        = \n| field           = [[Infectious disease (medical speciality)|Infectious disease]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = aspergillosis exposure\n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis''' ('''ABPA''') is a condition characterised by an exaggerated response of the [[immune system]] (a [[Hypersensitivity|hypersensitivity response]]) to the [[fungus]] ''[[Aspergillus]]'' (most commonly ''[[Aspergillus fumigatus]]''). It occurs most often in people with [[asthma]] or [[cystic fibrosis]]. ''Aspergillus'' [[spore]]s are ubiquitous in soil and are commonly found in the [[sputum]] of healthy individuals. ''A. fumigatus'' is responsible for a spectrum of lung diseases known as [[aspergillosis|aspergilloses]].\n\nABPA causes [[airway]] [[inflammation]], leading to [[bronchiectasis]]\u2014a condition marked by abnormal dilation of the airways. Left untreated, the [[immune system]] and fungal spores can damage sensitive lung tissues and lead to scarring.\n\nThe exact criteria for the diagnosis of ABPA are not agreed upon. [[Chest X-ray]]s and [[CT scan]]s, raised blood levels of [[Immunoglobulin E|IgE]] and [[eosinophilia|eosinophil]]s, immunological tests for ''Aspergillus'' together with sputum [[Gram staining|staining]] and [[sputum culture]]s can be useful. Treatment consists of [[corticosteroids]] and [[antifungal medication]]s.\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nAlmost all patients have clinically diagnosed [[asthma]],<ref name=Rosenberg1977>{{cite journal|last=Rosenberg|first=M|author2=Patterson, R|author3= Mintzer, R|author4= Cooper, BJ|author5= Roberts, M|author6= Harris, KE|title=Clinical and immunologic criteria for the diagnosis of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=April 1977 |volume=86|issue=4|pages=405\u201314|pmid=848802|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-86-4-405}}</ref> and present with [[wheeze|wheezing]] (usually episodic in nature), [[cough]]ing, [[shortness of breath]] and [[exercise intolerance]] (especially in patients with [[cystic fibrosis]]).<ref name=Kousha2011>{{cite journal|last=Kousha|first=M|author2=Tadi, R|author3= Soubani, AO|title=Pulmonary aspergillosis: a clinical review|journal=European Respiratory Review|date=1 September 2011 |volume=20|issue=121|pages=156\u201374|pmid=21881144|doi=10.1183/09059180.00001011}}</ref><ref name=Greenberger2002>{{cite journal|last=Greenberger|first=PA|title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|date=November 2002 |volume=110|issue=5|pages=685\u201392|pmid=12417875|doi=10.1067/mai.2002.130179}}</ref> Moderate and severe cases have symptoms suggestive of [[bronchiectasis]], in particular thick [[sputum]] production (often containing brown [[mucus|mucus plugs]]), as well as symptoms mirroring recurrent infection such as [[pleurisy|pleuritic]] [[chest pain]] and [[fever]]. Patients with asthma and symptoms of ongoing infection, who do not respond to antibiotic treatment, should be suspected of ABPA.<ref name=Kousha2011/>\n\n==Pathophysiology==\n''Aspergillus'' [[spore]]s are small (2\u20133 \u03bcm in diameter) and can penetrate deep into the respiratory system to the [[Pulmonary alveolus|alveolar]] level.<ref name=Hohl2007>{{cite journal|last=Hohl|first=TM|author2=Feldmesser, M|title=Aspergillus fumigatus: principles of pathogenesis and host defense|journal=Eukaryotic Cell|date=November 2007 |volume=6|issue=11|pages=1953\u201363|pmid=17890370|doi=10.1128/EC.00274-07|pmc=2168400}}</ref><ref name=Deacon2009>{{cite journal|last=Deacon|first=L.J.|author2=Pankhurst, L.J.|author3=Drew, G.H.|author4=Hayes, E.T.|author5=Jackson, S.|author6=Longhurst, P.J.|author7=Longhurst, J.W.S.|author8=Liu, J.|author9=Pollard, S.J.T.|author10= Tyrrel, S.F.|title=Particle size distribution of airborne Aspergillus fumigatus spores emitted from compost using membrane filtration|journal=Atmospheric Environment|date=November 2009|volume=43|issue=35|pages=5698\u20135701|doi=10.1016/j.atmosenv.2009.07.042|bibcode=2009AtmEn..43.5698D}}</ref> In healthy people, [[Innate immune system|innate]] and [[adaptive immune system|adaptive]] immune responses are triggered by various immune cells (notably [[neutrophil]]s, resident alveolar [[macrophage]]s and [[dendrites|dendritic cells]]) drawn to the site of infection by numerous [[inflammation|inflammatory]] [[cytokine]]s and neutrophilic attractants (such as [[CXCR2]] receptor ligands).<ref name=Brown2007>{{cite book|editor-last=Brown|editor-first=Gordon D.|title=Immunology of fungal infections|year=2007|publisher=Springer|location=Dordrecht|isbn=978-1-4020-5492-1|pages=5\u2013148|edition=Online-Ausg.|editor2=Netea, Mihai G.}}</ref> In this situation, [[mucociliary clearance]] is initiated and spores are successfully [[phagocytosis|phagocytosed]], clearing the infection from the host.<ref name=Hohl2007/><ref name=Moss2005>{{cite journal|last=Moss|first=RB|title=Pathophysiology and immunology of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Medical Mycology|date=May 2005 |volume=43 Suppl 1|pages=S203\u20136|pmid=16110813|doi=10.1080/13693780500052255|citeseerx=10.1.1.585.3463}}</ref>\n\nIn people with predisposing lung diseases\u2014such as persistent [[asthma]] or [[cystic fibrosis]] (or rarer diseases such as [[chronic granulomatous disease]] or [[Hyper-IgE syndrome]])\u2014several factors lead to an increased risk of ABPA.<ref name=Agarwal2013/> These include immune factors (such as [[atopy]] or immunogenic [[human leukocyte antigen|HLA]]-restricted [[phenotypes]]),<ref name=Antunes2010>{{cite journal|last=Antunes|first=J|author2=Fernandes, A|author3= Borrego, LM|author4= Leiria-Pinto, P|author5= Cavaco, J|title=Cystic fibrosis, atopy, asthma and ABPA|journal=Allergologia et Immunopathologia|date=September\u2013October 2010 |volume=38|issue=5|pages=278\u201384|pmid=20675033|doi=10.1016/j.aller.2010.06.002|hdl=10400.17/1668|url=http://repositorio.chlc.min-saude.pt/bitstream/10400.17/1668/1/Allergol%20Immunopathol%202010_278.pdf}}</ref><ref name=Muro2013>{{cite journal|last=Muro|first=M|author2=Mondejar-L\u00f3pez, P|author3= Moya-Quiles, MR|author4= Salgado, G|author5= Pastor-Vivero, MD|author6= Lopez-Hernandez, R|author7= Boix, F|author8= Campillo, JA|author9= Minguela, A|author10= Garcia-Alonso, A|author11= S\u00e1nchez-Sol\u00eds, M|author12= \u00c1lvarez-L\u00f3pez, MR|title=HLA-DRB1 and HLA-DQB1 genes on susceptibility to and protection from allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis in patients with cystic fibrosis|journal=Microbiology and Immunology|date=March 2013 |volume=57|issue=3|pages=193\u20137|pmid=23278646|doi=10.1111/1348-0421.12020}}</ref> as well as [[genetics|genetic]] factors (such as [[Cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator|CFTR gene]] mutations in both asthmatics and cystic fibrosis patients).<ref name=Marchand2001>{{cite journal|last=Marchand|first=E|author2=Verellen-Dumoulin, C|author3=Mairesse, M|author4=Delaunois, L|author5=Brancaleone, P|author6=Rahier, JF|author7= Vandenplas, O|title=Frequency of cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator gene mutations and 5T allele in patients with allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Chest|date=March 2001 |volume=119|issue=3|pages=762\u20137|pmid=11243954|doi=10.1378/chest.119.3.762}}</ref> By allowing ''Aspergillus'' spores to persist in pulmonary tissues, it permits successful [[germination]] which leads to [[hyphae]] growing in mucus plugs.<ref name=Moss2005/>\n\nThere are [[hypersensitivity]] responses, both a type I response (atopic, with formation of [[immunoglobulin]] E, or IgE) and a type III hypersensitivity response (with formation of [[immunoglobulin G]], or IgG).<ref name=Moss2005/><ref name=Chitkara2001>{{cite journal|last=Chitkara|first=RK|author2=Sarinas, PS|author3=Fick RB Jr|title=Immunoglobulin-E and anti-IgE treatment in lung disease|journal=Monaldi Archives for Chest Disease |date=December 2001 |volume=56|issue=6|pages=514\u201320|pmid=11980283}}</ref> The reaction of IgE with ''Aspergillus'' [[antigen]]s results in [[Degranulation#Mast cells|mast cell degranulation]] with [[bronchoconstriction]] and increased [[vascular permeability|capillary permeability]].<ref name=Mathias2009>{{cite journal|last=Mathias|first=CB|author2=Freyschmidt, EJ|author3=Caplan, B|author4=Jones, T|author5=Poddighe, D|author6=Xing, W|author7=Harrison, KL|author8=Gurish, MF|author9= Oettgen, HC|title=IgE influences the number and function of mature mast cells, but not progenitor recruitment in allergic pulmonary inflammation |journal=Journal of Immunology|date=15 February 2009 |volume=182|issue=4|pages=2416\u201324|pmid=19201896|pmc=2653867|doi=10.4049/jimmunol.0801569}}</ref> [[Immune complex]]es (a type III reaction) and inflammatory cells are deposited within the [[mucous membrane]]s of the airways, leading to [[necrosis]] (tissue death) and [[eosinophil]]ic infiltration.<ref name=Moss2005/> Type 2 [[T helper cell]]s appear to play an important role in ABPA due to an increased sensitivity to [[interleukin 4|interleukin (IL) 4]] and [[interleukin 5|IL-5]]. These cytokines up-regulate mast cell degranulation, exacerbating respiratory decline.<ref name=Knutsen2004>{{cite journal|last=Knutsen|first=AP|author2=Hutchinson PS |author3=Albers GM |author4=Consolino J |author5=Smick J |author6=Kurup VP |title=Increased sensitivity to IL-4 in cystic fibrosis patients with allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Allergy|volume=59|issue=1|pages=81\u201387|pmid=14674938|date=Jan 2004|doi=10.1046/j.1398-9995.2003.00129.x}}</ref><ref name=Muller2012>{{cite journal|last=M\u00fcller|first=U|author2=Piehler D|author3=Stenzel W|author4=K\u00f6hler G|author5=Frey O|author6=Held J|author7=Grahnert A|author8=Richter T|author9= Eschke M|author10=Kamradt T|author11=Brombacher F|author12=Alber G|title=Lack of IL-4 receptor expression on T helper cells reduces T helper 2 cell polyfunctionality and confers resistance in allergic bronchopulmonary mycosis|journal=Mucosal Immunology|volume=5|issue=3|pages=299\u2013310|pmid=22333910|doi=10.1038/mi.2012.9|year=2012}}</ref><ref name=Skov1999>{{cite journal|last=Skov|first=M|author2=Poulsen LK |author3=Koch C |title=Increased antigen-specific Th-2 response in allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis (ABPA) in patients with cystic fibrosis|journal=Pediatr Pulmonol|volume=27|issue=2|pages=74\u201379|pmid=10088929|date=Feb 1999|doi=10.1002/(sici)1099-0496(199902)27:2<74::aid-ppul2>3.0.co;2-l}}</ref>\n\n''Aspergillus'' also utilises a number of factors to continue evading host responses, notably the use of [[protease|proteolytic enzymes]] that interrupt IgG antibodies aimed towards it. Another important feature is its ability to interact and integrate with [[epithelium|epithelial]] surfaces, which results in massive pro-inflammatory counter-response by the immune system involving [[interleukin 6|IL-6]], [[interleukin 8|IL-8]] and MCP-1 (a [[CCL2]] receptor ligand). Proteases released by both the fungus and neutrophils induce further injury to the respiratory epithelium, leading to initiation of repair mechanisms (such as an influx of [[serum (blood)|serum]] and [[extracellular matrix]] (ECM) proteins) at the site of infection. Aspergillus spores and hyphae can interact with ECM proteins, and it is hypothesised that this process facilitates the binding of spores to damaged respiratory sites.<ref name=Moss2005/><ref name=Kauffman2003>{{cite journal|last=Kauffman|first=HF|title=Immunopathogenesis of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis and airway remodeling|journal=Frontiers in Bioscience|date=1 January 2003 |volume=8|issue=5|pages=e190\u20136|pmid=12456379|doi=10.2741/990}}</ref>\n\nAs concentrations of ''Aspergillus'' proteases increase, the immunological effect switches from pro-inflammatory to inhibitory, and further reduces phagocytic ability to clear ''Aspergillus''. Ultimately, repeated acute episodes lead to wider scale damage of pulmonary structures ([[parenchyma]]) and function via irreversible lung remodelling. Left untreated, this manifests as progressive [[bronchiectasis]] and [[pulmonary fibrosis]] that is often seen in the [[Human lung#Lobes|upper lobes]], and can give rise to a similar [[radiology|radiological]] appearance to that produced by [[tuberculosis]].<ref name=Kauffman2003/><ref name=Collins2001>{{cite journal|last=Collins|first=J|title=CT signs and patterns of lung disease|journal=Radiologic Clinics of North America|date=November 2001 |volume=39|issue=6|pages=1115\u201335|pmid=11699664|doi=10.1016/s0033-8389(05)70334-1}}</ref>\n\n==Diagnosis==\nThe exact criteria for the diagnosis of ABPA are not yet universally agreed upon, though working groups have proposed specific guidelines.<ref name=Agarwal2013>{{cite journal|last=Agarwal|first=R|author2=Chakrabarti, A|author3=Shah, A|author4=Gupta, D|author5=Meis, JF|author6=Guleria, R|author7=Moss, R|author8=Denning, DW|author9= ABPA complicating asthma ISHAM working, group|title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis: review of literature and proposal of new diagnostic and classification criteria|journal=Clinical and Experimental Allergy|date=August 2013 |volume=43|issue=8|pages=850\u201373|pmid=23889240|doi=10.1111/cea.12141}}</ref><ref name=Greenberger1982>{{cite journal|last=Patterson|first=R|author2=Greenberger, PA|author3= Radin, RC|author4= Roberts, M|title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis: staging as an aid to management|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=March 1982 |volume=96|issue=3|pages=286\u201391|pmid=7059089|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-96-3-286|citeseerx=10.1.1.1001.9839}}</ref> Minimal criteria include five factors:  the presence of asthma and/or cystic fibrosis, a positive skin test to ''Aspergillus'' sp., an IgE > 417 IU/mL (or kU/L), an increased specific IgE or IgG ''Aspergillus'' sp. antibodies, and the presence of infiltrates on a chest X-ray.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reddy|first=Ashwini|last2=Greenberger|first2=Paul A.|date=May\u2013June 2017|title=Allergic Bronchopulmonary Aspergillosis|journal=The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology: In Practice|volume=5|issue=3|pages=866\u2013867|doi=10.1016/j.jaip.2016.08.019|pmid=28483324|pmc=4306287}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Knutsen|first=Alan P.|last2=Bush|first2=Robert K.|last3=Demain|first3=Jeffrey G.|last4=Denning|first4=David W.|last5=Dixit|first5=Anupma|last6=Fairs|first6=Abbie|last7=Greenberger|first7=Paul A.|last8=Kariuki|first8=Barbara|displayauthors=et al|date=February 2012|title=Fungi and Allergic Lower Respiratory Tract Diseases|journal=Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|volume=129|issue=2|pages=280\u2013291|doi=10.1016/j.jaci.2011.12.970|pmid=22284927}}</ref>\n\nABPA should be suspected in patients with a predisposing [[lung disease]]\u2014most commonly [[asthma]] or [[cystic fibrosis]]\u2014 and is often associated with chronic airway limitation (CAL). Patients generally present with symptoms of recurrent infection such as [[fever]], but do not respond to conventional antibiotic therapy. Poorly-controlled asthma is a common finding, with a case series only finding 19% of ABPA patients with well-controlled asthma. [[Wheeze|Wheezing]] and [[hemoptysis]] (coughing up blood) are common features, and [[mucus|mucus plugging]] is seen in 31&ndash;69% of patients.<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\n===Blood tests and serology===\nThe first stage involves exposing the skin to Aspergillus fumigatus antigens; an immediate reaction is hallmark of ABPA.<ref name=Hogan2011>{{cite journal|last=Hogan|first=C|author2=Denning, DW|title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis and related allergic syndromes|journal=Seminars in Respiratory and Critical Care Medicine|date=December 2011 |volume=32|issue=6|pages=682\u201392|pmid=22167396|doi=10.1055/s-0031-1295716}}</ref> The test should be performed first by skin prick testing, and if negative followed with an intradermal injection. The overall sensitivity of the procedure is around 90%, though up to 40% of asthmatic patients without ABPA can still show some sensitivity to Aspergillus antigens (a phenomenon likely linked to a less severe form of ABPA termed severe asthma with fungal sensitization (SAFS)).<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\nSerum blood tests are an important [[biomarker|marker]] of disease severity, and are also useful for the primary diagnosis of ABPA. When serum IgE is normal (and patients are not being treated by [[glucocorticoid]] medications), ABPA is excluded as the cause of symptoms. A raised IgE increases suspicion, though there is no universally accepted cut-off value. Values can be stated in [[international units]] (IU/mL) or ng/mL, where 1 IU is equal to 2.4&nbsp;ng/mL. Since studies began documenting IgE levels in ABPA during the 1970s, various cut-offs between 833\u20131000 IU/mL have been employed to both exclude ABPA and to warrant further serological testing. The current consensus is that a cut-off of 1000 IU/mL should be employed, as lower values are encountered in SAFS and asthmatic [[sensitization]].<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\nIgG antibody [[precipitin]] testing from serum is useful, as positive results are found in between 69\u201390% of patients, though also in 10% of asthmatics with and without SAFS. Therefore, it must be used in conjunction with other tests. Various forms exist, including [[enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay]] (ELISA) and fluorescent enzyme [[immunoassay]] (FEIA). Both are more sensitive than conventional [[counterimmunoelectrophoresis]]. IgG may not be entirely specific for ABPA, as high levels are also found in [[aspergillosis|chronic pulmonary aspergillosis]] (CPA) alongside more severe radiological findings.<ref name=Agarwal2013/><ref name=Bains2012>{{cite journal|last=Bains|first=SN|author2=Judson, MA|title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Clinics in Chest Medicine|date=June 2012 |volume=33|issue=2|pages=265\u201381|pmid=22640845|doi=10.1016/j.ccm.2012.02.003}}</ref>\n\nUntil recently, peripheral [[eosinophilia]] (high [[eosinophil]] counts) was considered partly indicative of ABPA. More recent studies show that only 40% of ABPA sufferers present with eosinophilia, and hence a low eosinophil count does not necessarily exclude ABPA; for example patients undergoing steroid therapy have lower eosinophil counts.<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\n===Radiological investigation===\nConsolidation and mucoid impaction are the most commonly described radiological features described in ABPA literature, though much of the evidence for consolidation comes from before the development of computed tomography (CT) scans. Tramline shadowing, finger-in-glove opacities and \u2018toothpaste shadows\u2019 are also prevalent findings.<ref name=Greenberger2012>{{cite journal|last=Greenberger|first=PA|title=Chapter 18: Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Allergy and Asthma Proceedings|date=May\u2013June 2012 |volume=33 Suppl 1|issue=3|pages=S61\u20133|pmid=22794691|doi=10.2500/aap.2012.33.3551}}</ref>\n\nWhen utilising high-resolution CT scans, there can be better assessment of the distribution and pattern of bronchiectasis within the lungs, and hence this is the tool of choice in the radiological diagnosis of ABPA. Central (confined to medial two-thirds of the medial half of the lung) bronchiectasis that peripherally tapers bronchi is considered a requirement for ABPA pathophysiology, though in up to 43% of cases there is considerable extension to the periphery of the lung.<ref name=\"Kousha2011\"/>\n\nMucoid impaction of the upper and lower airways is a common finding.<ref name=Kousha2011/> Plugs are hypodense but appear on CT with high attenuation (over 70 [[Hounsfield unit]]s<ref name=\"AgarwalSehgal2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Agarwal|first1=Ritesh|last2=Sehgal|first2=Inderpaul Singh|last3=Dhooria|first3=Sahajal|last4=Aggarwal|first4=Ashutosh|title=Radiologic Criteria for the Diagnosis of High-Attenuation Mucus in Allergic Bronchopulmonary Aspergillosis|journal=Chest|volume=149|issue=4|year=2016|pages=1109\u20131110|issn=0012-3692|doi=10.1016/j.chest.2015.12.043|pmid=27055707}}</ref>) in up to 20% of patients. Where present it is a strong diagnostic factor of ABPA and distinguishes symptoms from other causes of bronchiectasis.<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\nCT scans may more rarely reveal mosaic-appearance [[attenuation]], centrilobular [[lung nodule]]s, tree-in-bud opacities and pleuropulmonary [[fibrosis]] (a finding consistent with CPA, a disease with ABPA as a known precursor).<ref name=Kousha2011/> Rarely other manifestations can be seen on CT scans, including military nodular opacities, perihilar opacities (that mimic [[hilar lymphadenopathy]]), [[pleural effusion]]s and pulmonary masses. [[Cavitation]] and [[aspergilloma]] are rarer findings, not exceeding 20% of patients, and likely represent a shift from ABPA to CPA if accompanied by [[pleura]]l thickening or fibrocavitary disease.<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\n===Culture===\n[[Microbiological culture|Culturing]] [[fungi]] from sputum is a supportive test in the diagnosis of ABPA, but is not 100% [[Sensitivity and specificity#Specificity|specific]] for ABPA as ''A. fumigatus'' is ubiquitous and commonly isolated from lung expectorant in other diseases. Nevertheless, between 40\u201360% of patients do have positive cultures depending on the number of samples taken.<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\n===Staging===\nNew criteria by the ABPA Complicated Asthma ISHAM Working Group suggests a 6-stage criteria for the diagnosis of ABPA, though this is yet to be formalised into official guidelines.<ref name=\"Agarwal2013\" /> This would replace the current gold standard staging protocol devised by Patterson and colleagues.<ref name=\"Greenberger1982\" /> Stage 0 would represent an asymptomatic form of ABPA, with controlled asthma but still fulfilling the fundamental diagnostic requirements of a positive skin test with elevated total IgE (>1000 IU/mL). Stage 6 is an advanced ABPA, with the presence of type II respiratory failure or [[cor pulmonale|pulmonary heart disease]], with radiological evidence of severe fibrosis consistent with ABPA on a high-resolution CT scan. It must be diagnosed after excluding the other, reversible causes of [[acute respiratory failure]].<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\n==Treatment==\nUnderlying disease must be controlled to prevent exacerbation and worsening of ABPA, and in most patients this consists of managing their asthma or CF. Any other co-morbidities, such as sinusitis or rhinitis, should also be addressed.<ref name=Walsh2008>{{cite journal|last=Walsh|first=TJ|author2=Anaissie, EJ|author3= Denning, DW|author4= Herbrecht, R|author5= Kontoyiannis, DP|author6= Marr, KA|author7= Morrison, VA|author8= Segal, BH|author9= Steinbach, WJ|author10= Stevens, DA|author11= van Burik, JA|author12= Wingard, JR|author13= Patterson, TF|author14= Infectious Diseases Society of America|title=Treatment of aspergillosis: clinical practice guidelines of the Infectious Diseases Society of America|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases|date=1 February 2008 |volume=46|issue=3|pages=327\u201360|pmid=18177225|doi=10.1086/525258}}</ref>\n\n[[Hypersensitivity]] mechanisms, [[Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis#Pathophysiology|as described above]], contribute to progression of the disease over time and, when left untreated, result in extensive [[fibrosis]] of lung tissue. In order to reduce this, [[corticosteroid]] therapy is the mainstay of treatment (for example with [[prednisone]]); however, studies involving corticosteroids in ABPA are limited by small [[cohort (statistics)|cohort]]s and are often not [[double-blinded]]. Despite this, there is evidence that acute-onset ABPA is improved by corticosteroid treatment as it reduces episodes of [[Consolidation (medicine)|consolidation]]. There are challenges involved in long-term therapy with corticosteroids\u2014which can induce severe [[immune dysfunction]] when used chronically, as well as [[metabolism|metabolic]] disorders\u2014and approaches have been developed to manage ABPA alongside potential [[adverse effects]] from corticosteroids.<ref name=Walsh2008/><ref name=Mahdavinia2012>{{cite journal|last=Mahdavinia|first=M|author2=Grammer, LC|title=Management of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis: a review and update|journal=Therapeutic Advances in Respiratory Disease|date=June 2012 |volume=6|issue=3|pages=173\u201387|pmid=22547692|doi=10.1177/1753465812443094}}</ref>\n\nThe most commonly described technique, known as sparing, involves using an [[Antifungal medication|antifungal]] agent to clear spores from airways adjacent to corticosteroid therapy. The antifungal aspect aims to reduce fungal causes of bronchial inflammation, whilst also minimising the dose of corticosteroid required to reduce the immune system's input to disease progression. The strongest evidence (double-blinded, [[Randomized controlled trial|randomized]], [[Placebo-controlled study|placebo]]-controlled trials) is for [[itraconazole]] twice daily for four months, which resulted in significant clinical improvement compared to placebo, and was mirrored in CF patients. Using itraconazole appears to outweigh the risk from long-term and high-dose prednisone. Newer [[triazole]] drugs\u2014such as [[posaconazole]] or [[voriconazole]]\u2014have not yet been studied in-depth through [[clinical trial]]s in this context.<ref name=Walsh2008/><ref name=Mahdavinia2012/>\n\nWhilst the benefits of using corticosteroids in the short term are notable, and improve [[Quality of life (healthcare)|quality of life]] scores, there are cases of ABPA converting to [[Aspergillosis|invasive aspergillosis]] whilst undergoing corticosteroid treatment. Furthermore, in concurrent use with itraconazole, there is potential for [[drug interaction]] and the induction of [[Cushing syndrome]] in rare instances. Metabolic disorders, such as [[diabetes mellitus]] and [[osteoporosis]], can also be induced.<ref name=Walsh2008/><ref name=Mahdavinia2012/>\n\nIn order to mitigate these risks, corticosteroid doses are decreased biweekly assuming no further progression of disease after each reduction.  When no [[exacerbation]]s from the disease are seen within three months after discontinuing corticosteroids, the patient is considered to be in complete [[Remission (medicine)|remission]]. The exception to this rule is patients who are diagnosed with advanced ABPA; in this case removing corticosteroids almost always results in exacerbation and these patients are continued on low-dose corticosteroids (preferably on an alternate-day schedule).<ref name=Walsh2008/><ref name=Mahdavinia2012/>\n\nSerum IgE can be used to guide treatment, and levels are checked every 6\u20138 weeks after steroid treatment commences, followed by every 8 weeks for one year. This allows for a determination of baseline IgE levels, though it's important to note that most patients do not entirely reduce IgE levels to baseline. [[Chest X-ray]] or CT scans are performed after 1\u20132 months of treatment to ensure [[Infiltration (medical)|infiltrates]] are resolving.<ref name=Walsh2008/><ref name=Mahdavinia2012/>\n\n==Epidemiology==\nThere are limited national and international studies into the burden of ABPA, made more difficult by a non-standardized diagnostic criteria. Estimates of between 0.5\u20133.5% have been made for ABPA burden in asthma,<ref name=Stevens2003>{{cite journal |author=Stevens DA |title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis in cystic fibrosis\u2014state of the art: Cystic Fibrosis Foundation Consensus Conference |journal=Clin. Infect. Dis. |volume=37 Suppl 3 |issue= |pages=S225\u201364 |date=October 2003 |pmid=12975753 |doi= 10.1086/376525|url=http://www.journals.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/resolve?CID31034|name-list-format=vanc |author2= Moss RB |author3= Kurup VP |author4=Knutsen AP |displayauthors=3 |last5=Greenberger |first5=Paul |last6=Judson |first6=Marc A. |last7=Denning |first7=David W. |last8=Crameri |first8=Reto |last9=Brody |first9=Alan S. |last10=Light |first10=Michael |last11=Skov |first11=Marianne |last12=Maish |first12=William |last13=Mastella |first13=Gianni |author14=Participants in the Cystic Fibrosis Foundation Consensus Conference }}</ref><ref name=Denning2013>{{cite journal|last=Denning|first=DW|author2=Pleuvry, A|author3= Cole, DC|title=Global burden of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis with asthma and its complication chronic pulmonary aspergillosis in adults|journal=Medical Mycology|date=May 2013 |volume=51|issue=4|pages=361\u201370|pmid=23210682|doi=10.3109/13693786.2012.738312}}</ref> and 1\u201317.7% in CF.<ref name=Stevens2003/><ref name=Armstead>{{cite journal|last1=Armstead|first1=J|last2=Morris|first2=J|last3=Denning|first3=DW|title=Multi-Country Estimate of Different Manifestations of Aspergillosis in Cystic Fibrosis|journal=PLOS ONE|date=10 June 2014|volume=9|issue=6|pages=e98502|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0098502|pmid=24914809|pmc=4051580|bibcode=2014PLoSO...998502A}}</ref> Five national cohorts, detecting ABPA prevalence in asthma (based on [[Global Initiative for Asthma|GINA]] estimates),<ref name=GINA>{{Cite journal|url = http://www.ginasthma.org/local/uploads/files/GINABurdenReport_1.pdf|title = GINA|journal = Global Burden of Asthma|accessdate = February 5, 2014|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130509145734/http://www.ginasthma.org/local/uploads/files/GINABurdenReport_1.pdf|archive-date = 2013-05-09|url-status = dead}}</ref> were used in a recent meta-analysis to produce an estimate of the global burden of ABPA complicating asthma. From 193 million asthma sufferers worldwide, ABPA prevalence in asthma is estimated between the extremes of 1.35\u20136.77 million sufferers, using 0.7\u20133.5% attrition rates. A compromise at 2.5% attrition has also been proposed, placing global burden at around 4.8 million people affected. The Eastern Mediterranean region had the lowest estimated prevalence, with a predicted case burden of 351,000; collectively, the Americas had the highest predicted burden at 1,461,000 cases. These are likely underestimates of total prevalence, given the exclusion of CF patients and children from the study, as well as diagnostic testing being limited in less developed regions.<ref name=Denning2013/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 956\n| ICD10           = \n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|518.6}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = 103920\n| MedlinePlus     = 000070\n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| eMedicine_mult  = {{eMedicine2|radio|55}}\n| MeshID          = D001229\n| ICD10CM         = {{ICD10CM|B44.81}}\n| Orphanet        = 1164\n}}\n*[http://www.fungalresearchtrust.org Fungal Research Trust]\n*[http://www.aspergillus.org.uk Aspergillus Website]\n*[http://www.gpnotebook.co.uk/simplepage.cfm?ID=1100611584 Allergic Bronchopulmonary Aspergillosis] \u2014 GP Notebook\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080512002159/http://rad.usuhs.mil/medpix/medpix.html?mode=caption_search&srchstr=allergic+bronchopulmonary+aspergillosis#top/ Medpix. ABPA radiology pictures]\n\n{{Allergic conditions}}\n{{Mycoses}}\n{{Respiratory pathology}}\n{{Hypersensitivity and autoimmune diseases}}\n\n[[Category:Aspergillus|*]]\n[[Category:Animal fungal diseases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis\n| synonyms        = \n| field           = [[Infectious disease (medical speciality)|Infectious disease]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = aspergillosis exposure\n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis''' ('''ABPA''') is a condition characterised by an exaggerated response of the [[immune system]] (a [[Hypersensitivity|hypersensitivity response]]) to the [[fungus]] ''[[Aspergillus]]'' (most commonly ''[[Aspergillus fumigatus]]''). It occurs most often in people with [[asthma]] or [[cystic fibrosis]]. ''Aspergillus'' [[spore]]s are ubiquitous in soil and are commonly found in the [[sputum]] of healthy individuals. ''A. fumigatus'' is responsible for a spectrum of lung diseases known as [[aspergillosis|aspergilloses]].\n\nABPA causes [[airway]] [[inflammation]], leading to [[bronchiectasis]]\u2014a condition marked by abnormal dilation of the airways. Left untreated, the [[immune system]] and fungal spores can damage sensitive lung tissues and lead to scarring.\n\nThe exact criteria for the diagnosis of ABPA are not agreed upon. [[Chest X-ray]]s and [[CT scan]]s, raised blood levels of [[Immunoglobulin E|IgE]] and [[eosinophilia|eosinophil]]s, immunological tests for ''Aspergillus'' together with sputum [[Gram staining|staining]] and [[sputum culture]]s can be useful. Treatment consists of [[corticosteroids]] and [[antifungal medication]]s.\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nAlmost all patients have clinically diagnosed [[asthma]],<ref name=Rosenberg1977>{{cite journal|last=Rosenberg|first=M|author2=Patterson, R|author3= Mintzer, R|author4= Cooper, BJ|author5= Roberts, M|author6= Harris, KE|title=Clinical and immunologic criteria for the diagnosis of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=April 1977 |volume=86|issue=4|pages=405\u201314|pmid=848802|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-86-4-405}}</ref> and present with [[wheeze|wheezing]] (usually episodic in nature), [[cough]]ing, [[shortness of breath]] and [[exercise intolerance]] (especially in patients with [[cystic fibrosis]]).<ref name=Kousha2011>{{cite journal|last=Kousha|first=M|author2=Tadi, R|author3= Soubani, AO|title=Pulmonary aspergillosis: a clinical review|journal=European Respiratory Review|date=1 September 2011 |volume=20|issue=121|pages=156\u201374|pmid=21881144|doi=10.1183/09059180.00001011}}</ref><ref name=Greenberger2002>{{cite journal|last=Greenberger|first=PA|title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|date=November 2002 |volume=110|issue=5|pages=685\u201392|pmid=12417875|doi=10.1067/mai.2002.130179}}</ref> Moderate and severe cases have symptoms suggestive of [[bronchiectasis]], in particular thick [[sputum]] production (often containing brown [[mucus|mucus plugs]]), as well as symptoms mirroring recurrent infection such as [[pleurisy|pleuritic]] [[chest pain]] and [[fever]]. Patients with asthma and symptoms of ongoing infection, who do not respond to antibiotic treatment, should be suspected of ABPA.<ref name=Kousha2011/>\n\n==Pathophysiology==\n''Aspergillus'' [[spore]]s are small (2\u20133 \u03bcm in diameter) and can penetrate deep into the respiratory system to the [[Pulmonary alveolus|alveolar]] level.<ref name=Hohl2007>{{cite journal|last=Hohl|first=TM|author2=Feldmesser, M|title=Aspergillus fumigatus: principles of pathogenesis and host defense|journal=Eukaryotic Cell|date=November 2007 |volume=6|issue=11|pages=1953\u201363|pmid=17890370|doi=10.1128/EC.00274-07|pmc=2168400}}</ref><ref name=Deacon2009>{{cite journal|last=Deacon|first=L.J.|author2=Pankhurst, L.J.|author3=Drew, G.H.|author4=Hayes, E.T.|author5=Jackson, S.|author6=Longhurst, P.J.|author7=Longhurst, J.W.S.|author8=Liu, J.|author9=Pollard, S.J.T.|author10= Tyrrel, S.F.|title=Particle size distribution of airborne Aspergillus fumigatus spores emitted from compost using membrane filtration|journal=Atmospheric Environment|date=November 2009|volume=43|issue=35|pages=5698\u20135701|doi=10.1016/j.atmosenv.2009.07.042|bibcode=2009AtmEn..43.5698D}}</ref> In healthy people, [[Innate immune system|innate]] and [[adaptive immune system|adaptive]] immune responses are triggered by various immune cells (notably [[neutrophil]]s, resident alveolar [[macrophage]]s and [[dendrites|dendritic cells]]) drawn to the site of infection by numerous [[inflammation|inflammatory]] [[cytokine]]s and neutrophilic attractants (such as [[CXCR2]] receptor ligands).<ref name=Brown2007>{{cite book|editor-last=Brown|editor-first=Gordon D.|title=Immunology of fungal infections|year=2007|publisher=Springer|location=Dordrecht|isbn=978-1-4020-5492-1|pages=5\u2013148|edition=Online-Ausg.|editor2=Netea, Mihai G.}}</ref> In this situation, [[mucociliary clearance]] is initiated and spores are successfully [[phagocytosis|phagocytosed]], clearing the infection from the host.<ref name=Hohl2007/><ref name=Moss2005>{{cite journal|last=Moss|first=RB|title=Pathophysiology and immunology of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Medical Mycology|date=May 2005 |volume=43 Suppl 1|pages=S203\u20136|pmid=16110813|doi=10.1080/13693780500052255|citeseerx=10.1.1.585.3463}}</ref>\n\nIn people with predisposing lung diseases\u2014such as persistent [[asthma]] or [[cystic fibrosis]] (or rarer diseases such as [[chronic granulomatous disease]] or [[Hyper-IgE syndrome]])\u2014several factors lead to an increased risk of ABPA.<ref name=Agarwal2013/> These include immune factors (such as [[atopy]] or immunogenic [[human leukocyte antigen|HLA]]-restricted [[phenotypes]]),<ref name=Antunes2010>{{cite journal|last=Antunes|first=J|author2=Fernandes, A|author3= Borrego, LM|author4= Leiria-Pinto, P|author5= Cavaco, J|title=Cystic fibrosis, atopy, asthma and ABPA|journal=Allergologia et Immunopathologia|date=September\u2013October 2010 |volume=38|issue=5|pages=278\u201384|pmid=20675033|doi=10.1016/j.aller.2010.06.002|hdl=10400.17/1668|url=http://repositorio.chlc.min-saude.pt/bitstream/10400.17/1668/1/Allergol%20Immunopathol%202010_278.pdf}}</ref><ref name=Muro2013>{{cite journal|last=Muro|first=M|author2=Mondejar-L\u00f3pez, P|author3= Moya-Quiles, MR|author4= Salgado, G|author5= Pastor-Vivero, MD|author6= Lopez-Hernandez, R|author7= Boix, F|author8= Campillo, JA|author9= Minguela, A|author10= Garcia-Alonso, A|author11= S\u00e1nchez-Sol\u00eds, M|author12= \u00c1lvarez-L\u00f3pez, MR|title=HLA-DRB1 and HLA-DQB1 genes on susceptibility to and protection from allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis in patients with cystic fibrosis|journal=Microbiology and Immunology|date=March 2013 |volume=57|issue=3|pages=193\u20137|pmid=23278646|doi=10.1111/1348-0421.12020}}</ref> as well as [[genetics|genetic]] factors (such as [[Cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator|CFTR gene]] mutations in both asthmatics and cystic fibrosis patients).<ref name=Marchand2001>{{cite journal|last=Marchand|first=E|author2=Verellen-Dumoulin, C|author3=Mairesse, M|author4=Delaunois, L|author5=Brancaleone, P|author6=Rahier, JF|author7= Vandenplas, O|title=Frequency of cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator gene mutations and 5T allele in patients with allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Chest|date=March 2001 |volume=119|issue=3|pages=762\u20137|pmid=11243954|doi=10.1378/chest.119.3.762}}</ref> By allowing ''Aspergillus'' spores to persist in pulmonary tissues, it permits successful [[germination]] which leads to [[hyphae]] growing in mucus plugs.<ref name=Moss2005/>\n\nThere are [[hypersensitivity]] responses, both a type I response (atopic, with formation of [[immunoglobulin]] E, or IgE) and a type III hypersensitivity response (with formation of [[immunoglobulin G]], or IgG).<ref name=Moss2005/><ref name=Chitkara2001>{{cite journal|last=Chitkara|first=RK|author2=Sarinas, PS|author3=Fick RB Jr|title=Immunoglobulin-E and anti-IgE treatment in lung disease|journal=Monaldi Archives for Chest Disease |date=December 2001 |volume=56|issue=6|pages=514\u201320|pmid=11980283}}</ref> The reaction of IgE with ''Aspergillus'' [[antigen]]s results in [[Degranulation#Mast cells|mast cell degranulation]] with [[bronchoconstriction]] and increased [[vascular permeability|capillary permeability]].<ref name=Mathias2009>{{cite journal|last=Mathias|first=CB|author2=Freyschmidt, EJ|author3=Caplan, B|author4=Jones, T|author5=Poddighe, D|author6=Xing, W|author7=Harrison, KL|author8=Gurish, MF|author9= Oettgen, HC|title=IgE influences the number and function of mature mast cells, but not progenitor recruitment in allergic pulmonary inflammation |journal=Journal of Immunology|date=15 February 2009 |volume=182|issue=4|pages=2416\u201324|pmid=19201896|pmc=2653867|doi=10.4049/jimmunol.0801569}}</ref> [[Immune complex]]es (a type III reaction) and inflammatory cells are deposited within the [[mucous membrane]]s of the airways, leading to [[necrosis]] (tissue death) and [[eosinophil]]ic infiltration.<ref name=Moss2005/> Type 2 [[T helper cell]]s appear to play an important role in ABPA due to an increased sensitivity to [[interleukin 4|interleukin (IL) 4]] and [[interleukin 5|IL-5]]. These cytokines up-regulate mast cell degranulation, exacerbating respiratory decline.<ref name=Knutsen2004>{{cite journal|last=Knutsen|first=AP|author2=Hutchinson PS |author3=Albers GM |author4=Consolino J |author5=Smick J |author6=Kurup VP |title=Increased sensitivity to IL-4 in cystic fibrosis patients with allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Allergy|volume=59|issue=1|pages=81\u201387|pmid=14674938|date=Jan 2004|doi=10.1046/j.1398-9995.2003.00129.x}}</ref><ref name=Muller2012>{{cite journal|last=M\u00fcller|first=U|author2=Piehler D|author3=Stenzel W|author4=K\u00f6hler G|author5=Frey O|author6=Held J|author7=Grahnert A|author8=Richter T|author9= Eschke M|author10=Kamradt T|author11=Brombacher F|author12=Alber G|title=Lack of IL-4 receptor expression on T helper cells reduces T helper 2 cell polyfunctionality and confers resistance in allergic bronchopulmonary mycosis|journal=Mucosal Immunology|volume=5|issue=3|pages=299\u2013310|pmid=22333910|doi=10.1038/mi.2012.9|year=2012}}</ref><ref name=Skov1999>{{cite journal|last=Skov|first=M|author2=Poulsen LK |author3=Koch C |title=Increased antigen-specific Th-2 response in allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis (ABPA) in patients with cystic fibrosis|journal=Pediatr Pulmonol|volume=27|issue=2|pages=74\u201379|pmid=10088929|date=Feb 1999|doi=10.1002/(sici)1099-0496(199902)27:2<74::aid-ppul2>3.0.co;2-l}}</ref>\n\n''Aspergillus'' also utilises a number of factors to continue evading host responses, notably the use of [[protease|proteolytic enzymes]] that interrupt IgG antibodies aimed towards it. Another important feature is its ability to interact and integrate with [[epithelium|epithelial]] surfaces, which results in massive pro-inflammatory counter-response by the immune system involving [[interleukin 6|IL-6]], [[interleukin 8|IL-8]] and MCP-1 (a [[CCL2]] receptor ligand). Proteases released by both the fungus and neutrophils induce further injury to the respiratory epithelium, leading to initiation of repair mechanisms (such as an influx of [[serum (blood)|serum]] and [[extracellular matrix]] (ECM) proteins) at the site of infection. Aspergillus spores and hyphae can interact with ECM proteins, and it is hypothesised that this process facilitates the binding of spores to damaged respiratory sites.<ref name=Moss2005/><ref name=Kauffman2003>{{cite journal|last=Kauffman|first=HF|title=Immunopathogenesis of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis and airway remodeling|journal=Frontiers in Bioscience|date=1 January 2003 |volume=8|issue=5|pages=e190\u20136|pmid=12456379|doi=10.2741/990}}</ref>\n\nAs concentrations of ''Aspergillus'' proteases increase, the immunological effect switches from pro-inflammatory to inhibitory, and further reduces phagocytic ability to clear ''Aspergillus''. Ultimately, repeated acute episodes lead to wider scale damage of pulmonary structures ([[parenchyma]]) and function via irreversible lung remodelling. Left untreated, this manifests as progressive [[bronchiectasis]] and [[pulmonary fibrosis]] that is often seen in the [[Human lung#Lobes|upper lobes]], and can give rise to a similar [[radiology|radiological]] appearance to that produced by [[tuberculosis]].<ref name=Kauffman2003/><ref name=Collins2001>{{cite journal|last=Collins|first=J|title=CT signs and patterns of lung disease|journal=Radiologic Clinics of North America|date=November 2001 |volume=39|issue=6|pages=1115\u201335|pmid=11699664|doi=10.1016/s0033-8389(05)70334-1}}</ref>\n\n==Diagnosis==\nThe exact criteria for the diagnosis of ABPA are not yet universally agreed upon, though working groups have proposed specific guidelines.<ref name=Agarwal2013>{{cite journal|last=Agarwal|first=R|author2=Chakrabarti, A|author3=Shah, A|author4=Gupta, D|author5=Meis, JF|author6=Guleria, R|author7=Moss, R|author8=Denning, DW|author9= ABPA complicating asthma ISHAM working, group|title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis: review of literature and proposal of new diagnostic and classification criteria|journal=Clinical and Experimental Allergy|date=August 2013 |volume=43|issue=8|pages=850\u201373|pmid=23889240|doi=10.1111/cea.12141}}</ref><ref name=Greenberger1982>{{cite journal|last=Patterson|first=R|author2=Greenberger, PA|author3= Radin, RC|author4= Roberts, M|title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis: staging as an aid to management|journal=Annals of Internal Medicine|date=March 1982 |volume=96|issue=3|pages=286\u201391|pmid=7059089|doi=10.7326/0003-4819-96-3-286|citeseerx=10.1.1.1001.9839}}</ref> Minimal criteria include five factors:  the presence of asthma and/or cystic fibrosis, a positive skin test to ''Aspergillus'' sp., an IgE > 417 IU/mL (or kU/L), an increased specific IgE or IgG ''Aspergillus'' sp. antibodies, and the presence of infiltrates on a chest X-ray.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Reddy|first=Ashwini|last2=Greenberger|first2=Paul A.|date=May\u2013June 2017|title=Allergic Bronchopulmonary Aspergillosis|journal=The Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology: In Practice|volume=5|issue=3|pages=866\u2013867|doi=10.1016/j.jaip.2016.08.019|pmid=28483324|pmc=4306287}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Knutsen|first=Alan P.|last2=Bush|first2=Robert K.|last3=Demain|first3=Jeffrey G.|last4=Denning|first4=David W.|last5=Dixit|first5=Anupma|last6=Fairs|first6=Abbie|last7=Greenberger|first7=Paul A.|last8=Kariuki|first8=Barbara|displayauthors=et al|date=February 2012|title=Fungi and Allergic Lower Respiratory Tract Diseases|journal=Journal of Allergy and Clinical Immunology|volume=129|issue=2|pages=280\u2013291|doi=10.1016/j.jaci.2011.12.970|pmid=22284927}}</ref>\n\nABPA should be suspected in patients with a predisposing [[lung disease]]\u2014most commonly [[asthma]] or [[cystic fibrosis]]\u2014 and is often associated with chronic airway limitation (CAL). Patients generally present with symptoms of recurrent infection such as [[fever]], but do not respond to conventional antibiotic therapy. Poorly-controlled asthma is a common finding, with a case series only finding 19% of ABPA patients with well-controlled asthma. [[Wheeze|Wheezing]] and [[hemoptysis]] (coughing up blood) are common features, and [[mucus|mucus plugging]] is seen in 31&ndash;69% of patients.<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\n===Blood tests and serology===\nThe first stage involves exposing the skin to Aspergillus fumigatus antigens; an immediate reaction is hallmark of ABPA.<ref name=Hogan2011>{{cite journal|last=Hogan|first=C|author2=Denning, DW|title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis and related allergic syndromes|journal=Seminars in Respiratory and Critical Care Medicine|date=December 2011 |volume=32|issue=6|pages=682\u201392|pmid=22167396|doi=10.1055/s-0031-1295716}}</ref> The test should be performed first by skin prick testing, and if negative followed with an intradermal injection. The overall sensitivity of the procedure is around 90%, though up to 40% of asthmatic patients without ABPA can still show some sensitivity to Aspergillus antigens (a phenomenon likely linked to a less severe form of ABPA termed severe asthma with fungal sensitization (SAFS)).<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\nSerum blood tests are an important [[biomarker|marker]] of disease severity, and are also useful for the primary diagnosis of ABPA. When serum IgE is normal (and patients are not being treated by [[glucocorticoid]] medications), ABPA is excluded as the cause of symptoms. A raised IgE increases suspicion, though there is no universally accepted cut-off value. Values can be stated in [[international units]] (IU/mL) or ng/mL, where 1 IU is equal to 2.4&nbsp;ng/mL. Since studies began documenting IgE levels in ABPA during the 1970s, various cut-offs between 833\u20131000 IU/mL have been employed to both exclude ABPA and to warrant further serological testing. The current consensus is that a cut-off of 1000 IU/mL should be employed, as lower values are encountered in SAFS and asthmatic [[sensitization]].<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\nIgG antibody [[precipitin]] testing from serum is useful, as positive results are found in between 69\u201390% of patients, though also in 10% of asthmatics with and without SAFS. Therefore, it must be used in conjunction with other tests. Various forms exist, including [[enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay]] (ELISA) and fluorescent enzyme [[immunoassay]] (FEIA). Both are more sensitive than conventional [[counterimmunoelectrophoresis]]. IgG may not be entirely specific for ABPA, as high levels are also found in [[aspergillosis|chronic pulmonary aspergillosis]] (CPA) alongside more severe radiological findings.<ref name=Agarwal2013/><ref name=Bains2012>{{cite journal|last=Bains|first=SN|author2=Judson, MA|title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Clinics in Chest Medicine|date=June 2012 |volume=33|issue=2|pages=265\u201381|pmid=22640845|doi=10.1016/j.ccm.2012.02.003}}</ref>\n\nUntil recently, peripheral [[eosinophilia]] (high [[eosinophil]] counts) was considered partly indicative of ABPA. More recent studies show that only 40% of ABPA sufferers present with eosinophilia, and hence a low eosinophil count does not necessarily exclude ABPA; for example patients undergoing steroid therapy have lower eosinophil counts.<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\n===Radiological investigation===\nConsolidation and mucoid impaction are the most commonly described radiological features described in ABPA literature, though much of the evidence for consolidation comes from before the development of computed tomography (CT) scans. Tramline shadowing, finger-in-glove opacities and \u2018toothpaste shadows\u2019 are also prevalent findings.<ref name=Greenberger2012>{{cite journal|last=Greenberger|first=PA|title=Chapter 18: Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis|journal=Allergy and Asthma Proceedings|date=May\u2013June 2012 |volume=33 Suppl 1|issue=3|pages=S61\u20133|pmid=22794691|doi=10.2500/aap.2012.33.3551}}</ref>\n\nWhen utilising high-resolution CT scans, there can be better assessment of the distribution and pattern of bronchiectasis within the lungs, and hence this is the tool of choice in the radiological diagnosis of ABPA. Central (confined to medial two-thirds of the medial half of the lung) bronchiectasis that peripherally tapers bronchi is considered a requirement for ABPA pathophysiology, though in up to 43% of cases there is considerable extension to the periphery of the lung.<ref name=\"Kousha2011\"/>\n\nMucoid impaction of the upper and lower airways is a common finding.<ref name=Kousha2011/> Plugs are hypodense but appear on CT with high attenuation (over 70 [[Hounsfield unit]]s<ref name=\"AgarwalSehgal2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Agarwal|first1=Ritesh|last2=Sehgal|first2=Inderpaul Singh|last3=Dhooria|first3=Sahajal|last4=Aggarwal|first4=Ashutosh|title=Radiologic Criteria for the Diagnosis of High-Attenuation Mucus in Allergic Bronchopulmonary Aspergillosis|journal=Chest|volume=149|issue=4|year=2016|pages=1109\u20131110|issn=0012-3692|doi=10.1016/j.chest.2015.12.043|pmid=27055707}}</ref>) in up to 20% of patients. Where present it is a strong diagnostic factor of ABPA and distinguishes symptoms from other causes of bronchiectasis.<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\nCT scans may more rarely reveal mosaic-appearance [[attenuation]], centrilobular [[lung nodule]]s, tree-in-bud opacities and pleuropulmonary [[fibrosis]] (a finding consistent with CPA, a disease with ABPA as a known precursor).<ref name=Kousha2011/> Rarely other manifestations can be seen on CT scans, including military nodular opacities, perihilar opacities (that mimic [[hilar lymphadenopathy]]), [[pleural effusion]]s and pulmonary masses. [[Cavitation]] and [[aspergilloma]] are rarer findings, not exceeding 20% of patients, and likely represent a shift from ABPA to CPA if accompanied by [[pleura]]l thickening or fibrocavitary disease.<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\n===Culture===\n[[Microbiological culture|Culturing]] [[fungi]] from sputum is a supportive test in the diagnosis of ABPA, but is not 100% [[Sensitivity and specificity#Specificity|specific]] for ABPA as ''A. fumigatus'' is ubiquitous and commonly isolated from lung expectorant in other diseases. Nevertheless, between 40\u201360% of patients do have positive cultures depending on the number of samples taken.<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\n===Staging===\nNew criteria by the ABPA Complicated Asthma ISHAM Working Group suggests a 6-stage criteria for the diagnosis of ABPA, though this is yet to be formalised into official guidelines.<ref name=\"Agarwal2013\" /> This would replace the current gold standard staging protocol devised by Patterson and colleagues.<ref name=\"Greenberger1982\" /> Stage 0 would represent an asymptomatic form of ABPA, with controlled asthma but still fulfilling the fundamental diagnostic requirements of a positive skin test with elevated total IgE (>1000 IU/mL). Stage 6 is an advanced ABPA, with the presence of type II respiratory failure or [[cor pulmonale|pulmonary heart disease]], with radiological evidence of severe fibrosis consistent with ABPA on a high-resolution CT scan. It must be diagnosed after excluding the other, reversible causes of [[acute respiratory failure]].<ref name=Agarwal2013/>\n\n==Treatment==\nUnderlying disease must be controlled to prevent exacerbation and worsening of ABPA, and in most patients this consists of managing their asthma or CF. Any other co-morbidities, such as sinusitis or rhinitis, should also be addressed.<ref name=Walsh2008>{{cite journal|last=Walsh|first=TJ|author2=Anaissie, EJ|author3= Denning, DW|author4= Herbrecht, R|author5= Kontoyiannis, DP|author6= Marr, KA|author7= Morrison, VA|author8= Segal, BH|author9= Steinbach, WJ|author10= Stevens, DA|author11= van Burik, JA|author12= Wingard, JR|author13= Patterson, TF|author14= Infectious Diseases Society of America|title=Treatment of aspergillosis: clinical practice guidelines of the Infectious Diseases Society of America|journal=Clinical Infectious Diseases|date=1 February 2008 |volume=46|issue=3|pages=327\u201360|pmid=18177225|doi=10.1086/525258}}</ref>\n\n[[Hypersensitivity]] mechanisms, [[Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis#Pathophysiology|as described above]], contribute to progression of the disease over time and, when left untreated, result in extensive [[fibrosis]] of lung tissue. In order to reduce this, [[corticosteroid]] therapy is the mainstay of treatment (for example with [[prednisone]]); however, studies involving corticosteroids in ABPA are limited by small [[cohort (statistics)|cohort]]s and are often not [[double-blinded]]. Despite this, there is evidence that acute-onset ABPA is improved by corticosteroid treatment as it reduces episodes of [[Consolidation (medicine)|consolidation]]. There are challenges involved in long-term therapy with corticosteroids\u2014which can induce severe [[immune dysfunction]] when used chronically, as well as [[metabolism|metabolic]] disorders\u2014and approaches have been developed to manage ABPA alongside potential [[adverse effects]] from corticosteroids.<ref name=Walsh2008/><ref name=Mahdavinia2012>{{cite journal|last=Mahdavinia|first=M|author2=Grammer, LC|title=Management of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis: a review and update|journal=Therapeutic Advances in Respiratory Disease|date=June 2012 |volume=6|issue=3|pages=173\u201387|pmid=22547692|doi=10.1177/1753465812443094}}</ref>\n\nThe most commonly described technique, known as sparing, involves using an [[Antifungal medication|antifungal]] agent to clear spores from airways adjacent to corticosteroid therapy. The antifungal aspect aims to reduce fungal causes of bronchial inflammation, whilst also minimising the dose of corticosteroid required to reduce the immune system's input to disease progression. The strongest evidence (double-blinded, [[Randomized controlled trial|randomized]], [[Placebo-controlled study|placebo]]-controlled trials) is for [[itraconazole]] twice daily for four months, which resulted in significant clinical improvement compared to placebo, and was mirrored in CF patients. Using itraconazole appears to outweigh the risk from long-term and high-dose prednisone. Newer [[triazole]] drugs\u2014such as [[posaconazole]] or [[voriconazole]]\u2014have not yet been studied in-depth through [[clinical trial]]s in this context.<ref name=Walsh2008/><ref name=Mahdavinia2012/>\n\nWhilst the benefits of using corticosteroids in the short term are notable, and improve [[Quality of life (healthcare)|quality of life]] scores, there are cases of ABPA converting to [[Aspergillosis|invasive aspergillosis]] whilst undergoing corticosteroid treatment. Furthermore, in concurrent use with itraconazole, there is potential for [[drug interaction]] and the induction of [[Cushing syndrome]] in rare instances. Metabolic disorders, such as [[diabetes mellitus]] and [[osteoporosis]], can also be induced.<ref name=Walsh2008/><ref name=Mahdavinia2012/>\n\nIn order to mitigate these risks, corticosteroid doses are decreased biweekly assuming no further progression of disease after each reduction.  When no [[exacerbation]]s from the disease are seen within three months after discontinuing corticosteroids, the patient is considered to be in complete [[Remission (medicine)|remission]]. The exception to this rule is patients who are diagnosed with advanced ABPA; in this case removing corticosteroids almost always results in exacerbation and these patients are continued on low-dose corticosteroids (preferably on an alternate-day schedule).<ref name=Walsh2008/><ref name=Mahdavinia2012/>\n\nSerum IgE can be used to guide treatment, and levels are checked every 6\u20138 weeks after steroid treatment commences, followed by every 8 weeks for one year. This allows for a determination of baseline IgE levels, though it's important to note that most patients do not entirely reduce IgE levels to baseline. [[Chest X-ray]] or CT scans are performed after 1\u20132 months of treatment to ensure [[Infiltration (medical)|infiltrates]] are resolving.<ref name=Walsh2008/><ref name=Mahdavinia2012/>\n\n==Epidemiology==\nThere are limited national and international studies into the burden of ABPA, made more difficult by a non-standardized diagnostic criteria. Estimates of between 0.5\u20133.5% have been made for ABPA burden in asthma,<ref name=Stevens2003>{{cite journal |author=Stevens DA |title=Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis in cystic fibrosis\u2014state of the art: Cystic Fibrosis Foundation Consensus Conference |journal=Clin. Infect. Dis. |volume=37 Suppl 3 |issue= |pages=S225\u201364 |date=October 2003 |pmid=12975753 |doi= 10.1086/376525|url=http://www.journals.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/resolve?CID31034|name-list-format=vanc |author2= Moss RB |author3= Kurup VP |author4=Knutsen AP |displayauthors=3 |last5=Greenberger |first5=Paul |last6=Judson |first6=Marc A. |last7=Denning |first7=David W. |last8=Crameri |first8=Reto |last9=Brody |first9=Alan S. |last10=Light |first10=Michael |last11=Skov |first11=Marianne |last12=Maish |first12=William |last13=Mastella |first13=Gianni |author14=Participants in the Cystic Fibrosis Foundation Consensus Conference }}</ref><ref name=Denning2013>{{cite journal|last=Denning|first=DW|author2=Pleuvry, A|author3= Cole, DC|title=Global burden of allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis with asthma and its complication chronic pulmonary aspergillosis in adults|journal=Medical Mycology|date=May 2013 |volume=51|issue=4|pages=361\u201370|pmid=23210682|doi=10.3109/13693786.2012.738312}}</ref> and 1\u201317.7% in CF.<ref name=Stevens2003/><ref name=Armstead>{{cite journal|last1=Armstead|first1=J|last2=Morris|first2=J|last3=Denning|first3=DW|title=Multi-Country Estimate of Different Manifestations of Aspergillosis in Cystic Fibrosis|journal=PLOS ONE|date=10 June 2014|volume=9|issue=6|pages=e98502|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0098502|pmid=24914809|pmc=4051580|bibcode=2014PLoSO...998502A}}</ref> Five national cohorts, detecting ABPA prevalence in asthma (based on [[Global Initiative for Asthma|GINA]] estimates),<ref name=GINA>{{Cite journal|url = http://www.ginasthma.org/local/uploads/files/GINABurdenReport_1.pdf|title = GINA|journal = Global Burden of Asthma|accessdate = February 5, 2014|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130509145734/http://www.ginasthma.org/local/uploads/files/GINABurdenReport_1.pdf|archive-date = 2013-05-09|url-status = dead}}</ref> were used in a recent meta-analysis to produce an estimate of the global burden of ABPA complicating asthma. From 193 million asthma sufferers worldwide, ABPA prevalence in asthma is estimated between the extremes of 1.35\u20136.77 million sufferers, using 0.7\u20133.5% attrition rates. A compromise at 2.5% attrition has also been proposed, placing global burden at around 4.8 million people affected. The Eastern Mediterranean region had the lowest estimated prevalence, with a predicted case burden of 351,000; collectively, the Americas had the highest predicted burden at 1,461,000 cases. These are likely underestimates of total prevalence, given the exclusion of CF patients and children from the study, as well as diagnostic testing being limited in less developed regions.<ref name=Denning2013/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB      = 956 \n|  ICD10           =  \n|  ICD9            = {{ICD9|518.6}}  \n|  ICDO            =  \n|  OMIM            = 103920  \n|  MedlinePlus     = 000070  \n|  eMedicineSubj   =  \n|  eMedicineTopic  =  \n|  eMedicine_mult  = {{eMedicine2|radio|55}}  \n|  MeshID          = D001229 \n}}\n*[http://www.fungalresearchtrust.org Fungal Research Trust]\n*[http://www.aspergillus.org.uk Aspergillus Website]\n*[http://www.gpnotebook.co.uk/simplepage.cfm?ID=1100611584 Allergic Bronchopulmonary Aspergillosis] \u2014 GP Notebook\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080512002159/http://rad.usuhs.mil/medpix/medpix.html?mode=caption_search&srchstr=allergic+bronchopulmonary+aspergillosis#top/ Medpix. ABPA radiology pictures]\n\n{{Allergic conditions}}\n{{Mycoses}}\n{{Respiratory pathology}}\n{{Hypersensitivity and autoimmune diseases}}\n\n[[Category:Aspergillus|*]]\n[[Category:Animal fungal diseases]]\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allergic_bronchopulmonary_aspergillosis"}
{"title_page": "Vasilios Rovas", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Vasilios \u201cVeloso\u201d Rovas\n| image =\n| fullname =\n| height = {{height|m=1.78}}\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1984|1|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Karditsa]], [[Greece]]\n| currentclub = [[Anagennisi Karditsa F.C.|Anagennisi Karditsa]]\n| clubnumber =\n| position = [[midfielder (association football)|Defensive Midfielder]]\n| years1  = 2003\u20132004\n| years2  = 2004\u20132006\n| years3  = 2006\u20132009 \n| years4  = 2009\u20132010 \n| years5  = 2010\n| years6  = 2010\u20132012\n| years7  = 2012\u20132013\n| years8  = 2013\n| years9  = 2013\u20132015\n| years10 = 2015\u20132017\n| years11 = 2017\u20132018\n| years12 = 2018\u20132019\n| years13 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs1  = [[Pannaxiakos F.C.|Pannaxiakos]] | caps1 =  | goals1 = \n| clubs2  = [[Proodeftiki F.C.|Proodeftiki]] | caps2 = 41 | goals2 = 0 \n| clubs3  = [[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]] | caps3 = 57| goals3 = 2 \n| clubs4  = [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris]] | caps4 = 6 | goals4 = 0  \n| clubs5  = \u2192 [[PAS Giannina]]  (loan) | caps5 = 11 | goals5 = 0 \n| clubs6  = [[OFI Crete]]| caps6 = 7| goals6 = 0 \n| clubs7  = [[Panionios G.S.S.|Panionios]]| caps7 = 24| goals7 = 0\n| clubs8  = [[Apollon Smyrni F.C.|Apollon Smyrni]]| caps8 = 19| goals8 = 0\n| clubs9  = [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]| caps9 = 38 | goals9 = 0\n| clubs10 = [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris]] | caps10 = 42 | goals10 = 0 \n| clubs11 = [[Asteras Amaliada F.C.|Asteras Amaliada]] | caps11 = 19 | goals11 = 0\n| clubs12 = [[Niki Volos]] | caps12 = 0 | goals12 = 0\n| clubs13 = [[Anagennisi Karditsa F.C.|Anagennisi Karditsa]] | caps13 = 0 | goals13 = 0\n| club-update = 04:15, 20 May 2017 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Vasilios \u201cVeloso\u201d Rovas''' ({{lang-el|\u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u201c\u0392\u03b5\u03bb\u03cc\u03c3\u03bf\u201d \u03a1\u03cc\u03b2\u03b1\u03c2}}) (born 6 January 1984 in [[Karditsa]], [[Greece]]) is a Greek [[football (soccer)|footballer]] who plays for Anagennisi Karditsa as a [[midfielder (association football)|defensive midfielder]].\n\n==Career==\n\nHis first football steps made to [[Proodeftiki F.C.|Proodeftiki]]. Then [[Atromitos Athens|Atromitos]] for three years, where he was most of the time, a key member of the lineup. In 2009, he signed to [[Aris F.C. (Thessaloniki)|Aris]], but failed to establish itself as a key and so was loaned [[PAS Giannina]] in the second half of season 2009\u201310. In August 2010 he went to [[OFI Crete|OFI]], where there was large contributor to the  team. In January 2012 he moved to [[Panionios F.C.|Panionios]]. There he stayed until December of that year, when he decided to leave to try his luck abroad, but the agreement with the team abroad was not completed, so continue career at [[Apollon Smyrni]], who at the end of the season was crowned champion B 'National Division and promoted to the Super League. On July 1, 2013, having remained free from Apollon, announced he's agreement with AEK, in his first year he participated in 18 league matches, while the second 16. In September 2015, after five years absence, he returned to [[Aris F.C. (Thessaloniki)|Aris]]<ref>http://www.gazzetta.gr/football/article/799890/ekleise-rova-o-aris</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n;AEK Athens\n*[[Football League (Greece)|Football League]] (1): [[2014\u201315 Football League (Greece)|2014\u201315]] (South Group)\n*[[Football League 2 (Greece)|Football League 2]] (1): [[2013\u201314 Football League 2|2013\u201314]] (6th Group)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=person&id=19200 Scoresway.com Profile]\n*[http://www.epae.org/player.fds?categ=2&team=13&player=8901&pagecode=04.02.02&langid=1 Profile at epae.org]\n*[http://www.onsports.gr/onstats/soccer/player/557-Rovas-Basilis Profile] at Onsports.gr\n*[http://guardian.touch-line.com/StatsCentre.asp?Lang=0&CTID=31&CPID=76&pStr=Player&PLID=200361&TEID=673 Guardian Football]\n\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rovas, Vasilios}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Football League (Greece) players]]\n[[Category:Proodeftiki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Niki Volou FC players]]\n[[Category:Atromitos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aris Thessaloniki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAS Giannina F.C. players]]\n[[Category:OFI Crete F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Panionios F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Apollon Smyrni F.C. players]]\n[[Category:AEK Athens F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n\n{{Greece-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Vasilios \u201cVeloso\u201d Rovas\n| image =\n| fullname =\n| height = {{height|m=1.78}}\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1984|1|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Karditsa]], [[Greece]]\n| currentclub = [[Anagennisi Karditsa F.C.|Anagennisi Karditsa]]\n| clubnumber =\n| position = [[midfielder (association football)|Defensive Midfielder]]\n| years1  = 2003\u20132004\n| years2  = 2004\u20132006\n| years3  = 2006\u20132009 \n| years4  = 2009\u20132010 \n| years5  = 2010\n| years6  = 2010\u20132012\n| years7  = 2012\u20132013\n| years8  = 2013\n| years9  = 2013\u20132015\n| years10 = 2015\u20132017\n| years11 = 2017\u20132018\n| years12 = 2018\u20132019\n| years13 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs1  = [[Pannaxiakos F.C.|Pannaxiakos]] | caps1 =  | goals1 = \n| clubs2  = [[Proodeftiki F.C.|Proodeftiki]] | caps2 = 41 | goals2 = 0 \n| clubs3  = [[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]] | caps3 = 57| goals3 = 2 \n| clubs4  = [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris]] | caps4 = 6 | goals4 = 0  \n| clubs5  = \u2192 [[PAS Giannina]]  (loan) | caps5 = 11 | goals5 = 0 \n| clubs6  = [[OFI Crete]]| caps6 = 7| goals6 = 0 \n| clubs7  = [[Panionios G.S.S.|Panionios]]| caps7 = 24| goals7 = 0\n| clubs8  = [[Apollon Smyrni F.C.|Apollon Smyrni]]| caps8 = 19| goals8 = 0\n| clubs9  = [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]| caps9 = 38 | goals9 = 0\n| clubs10 = [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris]] | caps10 = 42 | goals10 = 0 \n| clubs11 = [[Asteras Amaliada F.C.|Asteras Amaliada]] | caps11 = 19 | goals11 = 0\n| clubs12 = [[Niki Volos]] | caps12 = 0 | goals12 = 0\n| clubs13 = [[Anagennisi Karditsa F.C.|Anagennisi Karditsa]] | caps13 = 0 | goals13 = 0\n| club-update = 04:15, 20 May 2017 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Vasilios \u201cVeloso\u201d Rovas''' ({{lang-el|\u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u201c\u0392\u03b5\u03bb\u03cc\u03c3\u03bf\u201d \u03a1\u03cc\u03b2\u03b1\u03c2}}) (born 6 January 1984 in [[Karditsa]], [[Greece]]) is a [[Greece|Greek]] [[football (soccer)|footballer]] who plays for [[Anagennisi Karditsa F.C.|Anagennisi Karditsa]] as a [[midfielder (association football)|defensive midfielder]].\n\n==Career==\n\nHis first football steps made to [[Proodeftiki F.C.|Proodeftiki]]. Then [[Atromitos Athens|Atromitos]] for three years, where he was most of the time, a key member of the lineup. In 2009, he signed to [[Aris F.C. (Thessaloniki)|Aris]], but failed to establish itself as a key and so was loaned [[PAS Giannina]] in the second half of season 2009-10. In August 2010 he went to [[OFI Crete|OFI]], where there was large contributor to the  team. In January 2012 he moved to [[Panionios F.C.|Panionios]]. There he stayed until December of that year, when he decided to leave to try his luck abroad, but the agreement with the team abroad was not completed, so continue career at [[Apollon Smyrni]], who at the end of the season was crowned champion B 'National Division and promoted to the Super League. On July 1, 2013, having remained free from Apollon, announced he's agreement with AEK, in his first year he participated in 18 league matches, while the second 16. In September 2015, after five years absence, he returned to [[Aris F.C. (Thessaloniki)|Aris]]<ref>http://www.gazzetta.gr/football/article/799890/ekleise-rova-o-aris</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n;AEK Athens\n*[[Football League (Greece)|Football League]] (1): [[2014\u201315 Football League (Greece)|2014\u201315]] (South Group)\n*[[Football League 2 (Greece)|Football League 2]] (1): [[2013\u201314 Football League 2|2013\u201314]] (6th Group)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=person&id=19200 Scoresway.com Profile]\n*[http://www.epae.org/player.fds?categ=2&team=13&player=8901&pagecode=04.02.02&langid=1 Profile at epae.org]\n*[http://www.onsports.gr/onstats/soccer/player/557-Rovas-Basilis Profile] at Onsports.gr\n*[http://guardian.touch-line.com/StatsCentre.asp?Lang=0&CTID=31&CPID=76&pStr=Player&PLID=200361&TEID=673 Guardian Football]\n\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rovas, Vasilios}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Football League (Greece) players]]\n[[Category:Proodeftiki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Niki Volou FC players]] \n[[Category:Atromitos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aris Thessaloniki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAS Giannina F.C. players]]\n[[Category:OFI Crete F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Panionios F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Apollon Smyrni F.C. players]]\n[[Category:AEK Athens F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n\n{{Greece-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dewritech", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 2009-10 \u2192 2009\u201310", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vasilios_Rovas"}
{"title_page": "Ief Verbrugghe", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Ief Verbrugghe\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| full_name      =\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{bda|1975|7|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Tienen]], Belgium\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  = 2000\n| amateurteam1   = {{ct|LTS|2000}} ''(stagiaire)''\n| amateuryears2  =\n| amateurteam2   =\n| proyears1      = 2001\u20132004\n| proteam1       = {{ct|LTS|2000}}\n| proyears2      =\n| proteam2       =\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n'''Ief Verbrugghe''' (born 25 July 1975 in [[Tienen]]) is a Belgian former professional cyclist. He rode his entire career on the {{ct|LTS|2004}} team, and rode in four editions of the [[Giro d'Italia]]. He did not achieve any professional wins.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=114669 | title=Ief Verbrugghe | work=ProCyclingStats | accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is the younger brother of former cyclist [[Rik Verbrugghe]].\n\n==Major results==\n;1999\n: 3rd [[Cholet-Pays de Loire]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cycling Archives|7976}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verbrugghe, Ief}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Tienen]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-1970s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Ief Verbrugghe\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| full_name      =\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{bda|1975|7|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Tienen]], Belgium\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  = 2000\n| amateurteam1   = {{ct|LTS|2000}} ''(stagiaire)''\n| amateuryears2  =\n| amateurteam2   =\n| proyears1      = 2001\u20132004\n| proteam1       = {{ct|LTS|2000}}\n| proyears2      =\n| proteam2       =\n| majorwins      =\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n'''Ief Verbrugghe''' (born 25 July 1975 in [[Tienen]]) is a Belgian former professional cyclist. He rode his entire career on the {{ct|LTS|2004}} team, and rode in four editions of the [[Giro d'Italia]]. He did not achieve any professional wins.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=114669 | title=Ief Verbrugghe | work=ProCyclingStats | accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is the younger brother of former cyclist [[Rik Verbrugghe]].\n\n==Major results==\n;1999\n: 3rd [[Cholet-Pays de Loire]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cycling Archives|7976}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Verbrugghe, Ief}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:People from Tienen]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-1970s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ief_Verbrugghe"}
{"title_page": "Tunnelvision", "text_new": "{{other uses|Tunnel vision (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:Tunnelvision.jpg|thumb]]\n'''Tunnelvision''' is a 50 ft x 75 ft large [[trompe-l'\u0153il]] painting, by [[Blue Sky (artist)|Blue Sky]], on a building in [[Columbia, South Carolina]], USA, which shows a tunnel in original size. Tunnelvision looks very realistic.\n== External links ==\n* http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/tunnelvision\n\n{{coord|34.006753|-81.03203|type:landmark_region:US-SC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category: Murals in South Carolina]]\n[[Category: Culture of Columbia, South Carolina]]\n[[Category: Art in South Carolina]]\n\n\n{{art-stub}}\n{{ColumbiaSC-stub}}\n\nbutt\n", "text_old": "{{other uses|Tunnel vision (disambiguation)}}\n\n[[File:Tunnelvision.jpg|thumb]]\n'''Tunnelvision''' is a 50 ft x 75 ft large [[trompe-l'\u0153il]] painting, by [[Blue Sky (artist)|Blue Sky]], on a building in [[Columbia, South Carolina]], USA, which shows a tunnel in original size. Tunnelvision looks very realistic.\n== External links ==\n* http://www.atlasobscura.com/places/tunnelvision\n\n{{coord|34.006753|-81.03203|type:landmark_region:US-SC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Murals in South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Culture of Columbia, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Art in South Carolina]]\n\n\n{{art-stub}}\n{{ColumbiaSC-stub}}\n", "name_user": "75.43.48.172", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tunnelvision"}
{"title_page": "Treyarch", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Treyarch\n| logo = Treyarch logo.svg\n| logo_caption = \n| type = [[Subsidiary]]\n| industry = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1996}}\n| founders = Peter Akemann<br />Do\u011fan K\u00f6sl\u00fc\n| defunct = \n| location_city = [[Santa Monica]], [[California]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.treyarch.com/}}\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| locations = \n| area_served = \n| key_people = {{plainlist| \n* Mark Lamia (Chairman)\n* Dan Bunting (Studio co-head)<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/5/8/17316562/call-of-duty-black-ops-zombies-treyarch-interview |title = Meet the studio behind Call of Duty: Black Ops and Zombies mode|date = May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n| products = ''[[Call of Duty]]'' series (2005\u2013present)\n| num_employees = 620\n| parent = [[Activision]]\n}}\n\n'''Treyarch''' is an American [[video game developer]], founded in 1996 by Peter Akemann and Do\u011fan K\u00f6sl\u00fc, and acquired by [[Activision]] in 2001. Located in [[Santa Monica, California]], it is known for its work for the ''[[Call of Duty]]'' series, with some other games in the series developed by [[Infinity Ward]] and [[Sledgehammer Games]].\n\n==History==\nTreyarch was founded in 1996, the company was acquired by [[Activision]] in 2001.\n\nIn 2005, [[Gray Matter Interactive]] was merged into Treyarch.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/companies/gray-matter-studios|title=Gray Matter Studios Games|website=IGN|access-date=2016-05-20}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the 2007 [[Leipzig Games Convention]], Activision announced that Treyarch would be one of three developers behind their first [[James Bond]] based game, ''[[007: Quantum of Solace]]''. The game was released on October 31, 2008 in Europe and November 4, 2008 in North America. [[Vicarious Visions]] developed the [[Nintendo DS]] version and [[Eurocom]] developed the PlayStation 2 version. Treyarch is a major developer in the ''[[Call of Duty]]'' series.\n\n''Call of Duty: Black Ops II'' held the record for the largest entertainment launch in history in any form of entertainment, breaking the record within 24 hours of its release until it was surpassed by ''[[Grand Theft Auto V]]''.<ref>{{cite news|author=The Associated Press |url=http://www.cbc.ca/technology/story/2010/11/11/callofduty-video-record.html |title=CBC News \u2013 Technology & Science \u2013 Call of Duty breaks sales record |publisher=CBC |date=November 11, 2010 |accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref> Sales from the game worldwide reached US$650&nbsp;million within five days after its release.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=socalTECH|date=November 18, 2010|accessdate=November 22, 2010|title=Call of Duty Black Ops Sales Hit $650M|url=http://www.socaltech.com/call_of_duty_black_ops_sales_hit_6__m/s-0032376.html}}</ref> Treyarch worked on the [[Wii U]] version of ''[[Call of Duty: Ghosts]]'', in order to optimize it for the console.<ref>{{cite news|last=McElroy|first=Griffin|title=Call of Duty: Ghosts confirmed for Wii U launch on Nov. 5 (update)|url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/7/25/4556676/call-of-duty-ghosts-confirmed-for-wii-u-launch-on-nov-5|accessdate=30 July 2013|newspaper=Polygon|date=July 25, 2013}}</ref> Treyarch's most recently released video game is ''[[Call of Duty: Black Ops 4]]'', which was released on October 12, 2018.<ref name=RANT-2018-HOFFMEYER>{{cite news |last=Hoffmeyer |first=Corey |date=October 12, 2018 |title=Call of Duty: Black Ops 4 Early Reviews: Treyarch Nails It |url=https://screenrant.com/call-duty-black-ops-4-game-early-reviews/ |work=ScreenRant |location= |access-date=October 12, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Games developed==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Game !! Platform(s)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1998 || ''[[Olympic Hockey Nagano '98]]'' || [[Nintendo 64]]\n|-\n| ''[[Die by the Sword]]'' || rowspan=\"2\"| [[Microsoft Windows]]\n|-\n| ''[[Die by the Sword|Die by the Swo