idscomplete00vern}}\n: {{cite book|last=von Beckerath|first=J\u00fcrgen|author-link=J\u00fcrgen von Beckerath|year=1997|title=Chronologie des pharaonischen \u00c4gypten : die Zeitbestimmung der \u00e4gyptischen Geschichte von der Vorzeit bis 332 v. Chr.|language=German|location=Mainz am Rhein|publisher=Philipp von Zabern|series=M\u00fcnchner \u00e4gyptologische Studien|volume=46|isbn=978-3-8053-2310-9|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book |last=von Beckerath|first=J\u00fcrgen|year=1999 |title=Handbuch der \u00e4gyptischen K\u00f6nigsnamen|series=M\u00fcnchner \u00e4gyptologische Studien|issue=49|location=Mainz |publisher= Philip von Zabern|isbn= 978-3-8053-2591-2|language=German|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|last=Waddell|first=William Gillan|title=Manetho|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts; London|publisher=Harvard University Press; W. Heinemann|year=1971|series=Loeb classical library, 350|url=https://archive.org/stream/manethowithengli00maneuoft#page/n89/mode/2up|oclc=6246102|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|last=Yurco|first=Frank J.|chapter=Cult temples prior to the New Kingdom|pp=239\u2013242|year=1999|editor1-first=Kathryn A.|editor1-last=Bard|editor2-first=Steven|editor2-last=Blake Shubert|title=Encyclopedia of the Archeology of Ancient Egypt|location=New York|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-203-98283-9|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://xoomer.virgilio.it/francescoraf/hesyra/ssannals.htm The South Saqqara Stone: Sixth Dynasty Annals]\n\n{{Pharaohs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pepi I}}\n[[Category:Pepi I Meryre| ]]\n[[Category:24th-century BC Pharaohs]]\n[[Category:23rd-century BC Pharaohs]]\n[[Category:Pharaohs of the Sixth Dynasty of Egypt]]\n[[Category:24th-century BC rulers]]\n[[Category:23rd-century BC rulers]]\n[[Category:24th century BC in Egypt]]\n[[Category:23rd century BC in Egypt]]\n[[Category:23rd-century BC deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox pharaoh\n| Name=Pepi I Meryre \n| Image=PepiI-CopperStatue-Cropped.png\n|Caption=Lifesize copper statue of Pepi I, [[Cairo Museum]] \n| PrenomenHiero=\n| Prenomen=<center>Nefer za hor<br/>''Nfr z3 \u1e24r''<br/>''Perfect is the protection of Horus''{{sfn|Leprohon|2013|p=42}}<br/><hiero>M23:t-L2:t-<-G5-F35-V18-></hiero><br/>Meryre{{sfn|Leprohon|2013|p=236}}<br/>''Mry R\u02c1''<br/>''Beloved of Re''{{sfn|Leprohon|2013|p=42}}<hiero>M23:t-L2:t-<-N5-U6-M17-M17-></hiero>{{sfn|Clayton|1994|p=64}}</center>\n| NomenHiero=<hiero>Q3:Q3-M17-M17</hiero>\n| Nomen=<center>Pepi<br/>''ppy''{{sfn|Leprohon|2013|p=42}}{{sfn|Clayton|1994|p=64}}</center>\n| HorusHiero=<hiero>-mr-i-i-tA:tA-</hiero>\n| Horus=<center>Mery Tawy<br/>''mry t3wy''<br/>''Beloved of the Two Lands''{{sfn|Leprohon|2013|p=42}}</center>\n| NebtyHiero=<hiero>-mr-i-i-X:t*Z1-</hiero>\n| Nebty=<center>Mery Khet Nebti<br/>''mry \u1e96t nbty''<br/> ''Beloved of the Two Ladies' body''{{sfn|Leprohon|2013|p=42}}</center>\n| GoldenHiero=\n| Golden=<center>Biku Nebu<br/>''b\u1ec9kw nbw''<br/>''The triple falcons are golden''{{sfn|Leprohon|2013|p=42}}</center><br><center><hiero>-G7*G7*G7:nbw-</hiero></center>\n| Reign= Uncertain duration: 34 up to 53 years have been proposed, in the second half of the 24th century BC or early 23rd century BC{{efn|group=note|Dates proposed for Pepi I's reign: 2354\u20132310 BC,{{sfn|Verner|2001b|p=590}}{{sfn|Altenm\u00fcller|2001|p=602}} 2335\u20132285 BC,{{sfn|von Beckerath|1997|p=188}} 2332\u20132283 BC,{{sfn|Clayton|1994|p=64}} 2321\u20132287\nBC,{{sfn|Rice|1999|p=150}}{{sfn|M\u00e1lek|2000a|p=104}} 2289\u20132255 BC,{{sfn|MET Cylinder|2020}} 2285\u20132235 BC,{{sfn|von Beckerath|1997|p=188}} 2276\u20132228 BC.{{sfn|Hornung|2012|p=491}}}} \n|father = [[Teti]]\n| mother = [[Iput]]\n| Predecessor=[[Userkare]] \n| Successor=[[Merenre Nemtyemsaf I]] \n| Spouse=Weret-yamtes, [[Ankhesenpepi I]], [[Ankhesenpepi II]], [[Nubwenet]], [[Meritites IV]], [[Inenek-Inti]], Mehaa, [[Nedjeftet]] \n| Children=[[Merenre Nemtyemsaf I]]<small> \u2642</small>, [[Pepi II]]<small> \u2642</small>, Hornetjerkhet<small> \u2642</small>, Tetiankh<small> \u2642</small>, Neith<small> \u2640</small>, Iput<small> \u2640</small> \n| Dynasty=[[Sixth dynasty of Egypt|6th&nbsp;Dynasty]] \n| Burial= [[Pyramid of Pepi I]] in South [[Saqqara]] \n| Alt= Pepy, Phios, Phius, \u03c6\u03b9\u03cc\u03c2\n| coregency = with his son Merenre at the end of his reign\n}}\n\n'''Pepi I Meryre''' (also '''Pepy I''') was the third king of the [[Sixth dynasty of Egypt]], ruling for over 40 years during the second half of the 24th Century BC, toward the end of the [[Old Kingdom of Egypt|Old Kingdom period]]. Pepi I was the son of his second predecessor [[Teti]], ascending the throne only after the brief and enigmatic reign of the shadowy [[Userkare]]. Pepi's mother was queen [[Iput]], who may have been a daughter of [[Unas]], final ruler of the [[Fifth Dynasty|Fifth Dynasty of Egypt]].\n\nPepi seems to have faced the decline of the pharaoh's power, which he tried to buttress by forming alliances with the provincial nomarch of Abydos, two daughters of whom became queens of Egypt. Pepi's first [[throne name]] was ''Neferdjahor'' which the king later altered to ''Meryre'' meaning \"beloved of [[R\u00ea]]\".{{sfn|Grimal|1992|p=84}}\n\nPepi was succeeded by his son [[Merenre Nemtyemsaf I]], who reigned only briefly. He was in turn succeeded by [[Pepi II]], who may have been another son of Pepi I by [[Ankhesenpepi II]], although he could instead be a grandson of Pepi I by Merenre I. Pepi II was the last great pharaoh of the Old Kingdom period.\n\n==Family==\n===Parents===\nPepi was the son of [[Teti]] and queen [[Iput]],{{sfn|Dodson|Hilton|2004|pp=64 \u2013 65 & 76}} who may have been a daughter of [[Unas]] the last pharaoh of the Fifth Dynasty.{{sfn|Verner|2001b|p=590}} That Pepi was indeed a son of Iput is demonstrated by a relief on a decree uncovered in Koptos, which mentions Iput as Pepi's mother.{{sfn|Dodson|Hilton|2004|p=76}}\n\n===Consorts===\n[[File:Queen_of_Pepy_II.jpg|thumb|upright|Ankhesenpepi II shown on a relief from her mortuary temple]]\nAt least eight consorts of Pepi I have been identified. These include [[Meritites IV]], [[Nubwenet]] and [[Inenek-Inti]], who are buried in pyramids adjacent to that of Pepi,{{sfn|Leclant|1999|p=866}} Mehaa, who is named in the tomb of her son Hornetjerkhet, and a queen named [[Nedjeftet]] who is mentioned on relief fragments.{{sfn|Dodson|Hilton|2004|p=73}}. Pepi's most prominent wives were [[Ankhesenpepi I]] and [[Ankhesenpepi II]], both daughters of the nomarch of Abydos Khui and his wife [[Nebet]].{{sfn|Dodson|Hilton|2004|p=73}} A final queen, named Weret-Yamtes,{{sfn|Grimal|1992|p=83}} is known from the inscriptions uncovered in the tomb of Weni, an official serving Pepi. This queen apparently conspired against Pepi but was prosecuted when the conspiracy was discovered.{{sfn|Grimal|1992|pp=82\u201383}}\n\n===Children===\nPepi fathered at least three sons and a daughter. Ankhesenpepi I in all likelyhood bore him the future pharaoh [[Merenre Nemtyemsaf I]]. In an alternative hypothesis, Hans Goedicke has proposed that Merenre's mother was the queen Were-Yamtes, responsible for the harem conspiracy against Pepi I. In this hypothesis, Ankhesenpepi I was claimed to be Merenre's mother to safeguard Merenre's claim to the throne.{{sfn|Goedicke|1955|p=183}} Ankhesenpepi II was the mother of [[Pepi II Neferkare]],{{sfn|Dodson|Hilton|2004|p=76}} who was likely born at the very end of his father's reign given that he was only 6 upon ascending the throne after Merenre's own reign.{{sfn|Goedicke|1955|p=183}} Another son of Pepi with an as yet unidentified consort was Teti-ankh, meaning \"Teti lives\".{{sfn|Dodson|Hilton|2004|p=76}} Teti-ankh is known only from an ink inscription bearing his name discovered in Pepi's pyramid.{{sfn|Dodson|Hilton|2004|p=78}} Buried nearby is prince Hornetjerkhet, a son of Pepi with queen Mehaa.{{sfn|Dodson|Hilton|2004|p=76}} Pepi I's daughters include possibly [[Neith (wife of Pepi II)|Neith]] and [[Iput II]], both future wives of Pepi II.\n\n==Reign==\n[[File:Kneeling Statuette of Pepy I, ca. 2338-2298 B.C.E., 39.121.jpg|thumb|upright|Kneeling Statuette of Pepy I, [[Brooklyn Museum]]{{efn|group=note|catalog number 39.121}}]]\n\n===Political situation===\n====Acending the throne====\nPepi's accession to the throne might have occurred in times of discord, as his father Teti is said by Manetho to have been assassinated by his own bodyguards.{{sfn|Waddell|1971|p=53}}{{sfn|Rice|1999|p=150}} [[Naguib Kanawati]] has argued in support of Manetho's claim, noting for example that Teti's reign saw an important increase in the number of guards at the Egyptian court, with these becoming responsible for the everyday care of the king.{{sfn|Kanawati|2003|p=184}}\nAt the same time, the figures and names of several palace officials as represented in their tombs had been purposefully erased.{{sfn|Kanawati|2003|p=173}} The attempted [[damnatio memoriae]] targeted three men in particular, the [[Vizier (Ancient Egypt)|vizier]] Heri, the overseer of weapons Mereri and chief physician Seankhuiptah who may therefore be behind the murder.{{sfn|Hubschmann|2011|p=2}}\n\nPepi was by then perhaps too young a child to reign. In any case, he did not immediately succeed his father who was rather succeeded by king [[Userkare]]. Userkare's identity and relation with the royal family remains uncertain. It is possible that he served only as a regent with Pepi's mother Iput as Pepi reached adulthood,{{sfn|Grimal|1992|p=81}} or occupied the throne in the interregnum.{{sfn|Smith|1971|p=191}}\nSuch hypotheses are supported by the apparent lack of resistance against Pepi ultimately taking the throne.{{sfn|Grimal|1992|p=81}} Against this view however, Kanawati has argued that Userkare's reign length\u2014at no more than five years\u2014is too short for a regency and that a regent would not have assumed a full royal titulary as Userkare did nor would he be included in king lists.{{sfn|Kanawati|2003|p=184}} \n\nNonetheless, Pepi chose the Horus name of ''Mery-tawy'', meaning \"He who is loved by the two lands\", which Nicolas Grimal sees as an indication that he desired political appeasement.{{sfn|Grimal|1992|p=82}} Similarly, Pepi chose the throne name ''Nefersahor'', meaning \"Perfect is the protection of Horus\", which he only later changed to Meryre \"Beloved of Ra\".{{sfn|M\u00e1lek|2000a|p=104}} Although there seems not to be a direct relation between Userkare's brief reign and a later conspiracy in his harem, these events suggest some form of political instability at the time.{{sfn|Grimal|1992|p=82}}\n\n[[File:Cylinder Seal with the Name of Pepi I MET 17-5.jpg|thumb|upright|Turquoise cylinder seal of an official of Pepi I, \"Sole companion, lector priest, who does what is ordered [...] privy to the secret(s) of the king\"{{sfn|MET Cylinder|2020|loc=catalog number 17.5}}]]\n====Policies====\nIn a long trend that started earlier in the Fifth Dynasty, the Old Kingdom Egyptian state was the subject of increasing decentralization and regionalization. This process, well under way during Pepi I's reign, progressively weakened the king's primacy and ascendancy over his own administration and would ultimately result in the princedoms of the First Intermediate Period.{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|p=16}} Pepi seems to have developed several policies to counteract this, notably with the constructions of royal Ka chapels throughout Egypt,{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|p=16}}{{sfn|Fischer|1958|pp=330\u2013333}} to strengthen the royal presence in the provinces.{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|p=17}}\n\nLater in this reign, possibly around his 44th year on the throne,{{sfn|Goedicke|1955|p=183}} Pepi faced a conspiracy hatched by one of his harem consort, Weret-Yamtes. Although the precise nature of her crime is not reported by Weni who served as a judge during the subsequent trial, this at least shows that the person of the king was not untouchable anymore.{{sfn|M\u00e1lek|2000a|p=105}} According to Hans Goedicke, Weret-Yamtes may have been the mother of Merenre,{{sfn|Goedicke|1955|p=183}} while Nicolas Grimal sees this as highly unlikely, as Weret-Yamtes' son would have been punished together her.{{sfn|Grimal|1992|pp=82\u201383}} Perhaps in response to these events, late in his reign Pepi married two daughters of Khui, nomarch of Abydos.{{sfn|M\u00e1lek|2000a|pp=104\u2013105}} This may also have served to counteract the weakening of the king's authority over Middle and Upper Egypt by securing the allegiance of a powerful family.{{sfn|Smith|1971|p=192}} The political importance of this marriage is demonstrated by the fact that, for the first and last time until the 26th Dynasty some 1800 years later,  Khui's wife [[Nebet]], a woman, was made [[Vizier (Ancient Egypt)|vizier]] of Upper Egypt.{{sfn|Kanawati|2003|p=173}} Later, Khui's and Nebet's son [[Djau]] was made vizier as well. Pepi's marriages might be at the origin{{sfn|Yurco|1999|p=240}} of a trend, which continued during the later Sixth and [[Eighth Dynasty of Egypt|Eighth Dynasties]], in which the temple of [[Min (god)|Min]] in Koptos was the focus of much royal patronage.{{sfn|Goedicke|1955|p=183}} This is manifested by the [[Coptos Decrees]], which record successive pharaohs granting tax exemptions to the temple as well as official honors bestowed by the kings to the local ruling family while the Old Kingdom society was collapsing.{{sfn|Hayes|1946|pp=3\u201323}}\n\nThis part of Pepi's rule may not have been any less troubled than his early reign, as Kanawati conjectures that Pepi faced yet another conspiracy against him, in which his vizier [[Rawer (vizier)|Rawer]] could have been involved. To support his theory, Kanawati observes that Rawer's image in his tomb has been desecrated, with his name, hands and feet chiselled off, while this same tomb is dated to the second half of Pepi's reign on stylistic grounds.{{sfn|Kanawati|2003|p=177}} Kanawati further posits that the conspiracy may have aimed at having someone else designated heir to the throne at the expense of Merenre. Consequently to the failure of this conspiracy, Pepi I would have taken the drastic step of crowning Merenre during his own reign, thereby creating the earliest documented coregency of the history of Egypt.{{sfn|Kanawati|2003|p=177}} That such a coregency did indeed take place is indirectly supported by a gold pendant bearing the names of both Pepi I and Merenre I as kings, an inscription mentioning king Merenre in Hatnub which suggests that he counted his years of reign starting at some point during his father's reign and the copper statues of Hierakonpolis, discussed below.{{sfn|Smith|1971|p=192}}\n\n====Building activities====\n[[File:Hidden treasures 09.jpg|thumb|upright|Smaller copper statue representing Merenre or a young Pepi I, from Hierakonpolis]]\nPepi I built extensively throughout Egypt, mostly devoting the building efforts to local cults{{sfn|Hayes|1978|p=126}} and royal Ka chapels.{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|pp=16\u201317}}\nIn [[Dendera]], where a fragmentary statue of a seated Pepi I has been uncovered,{{sfn|Daumas|1952|pp=163\u2013172}} Pepi I restored the [[Dendera Temple complex|temple complex]] to the goddess [[Hathor]].{{sfn|Cauville|1999|p=298}}\nIn Abydos,{{sfn|O'Connor|1999|p=110}} he built a small rock cut chapel dedicated to the local god [[Khenti-Amentiu]],{{sfn|Kraemer|2017|p=13}} where he is referred to as \"Pepi, Son of Hathor of Dendera\".{{sfn|Kraemer|2017|p=1}} \nIn the same locality Pepi might also have had a small [[Ancient_Egyptian_conception_of_the_soul#k\ua723_\"double\"|Ka]]-chapel built for himself.{{sfn|Brovarski|1994|p=17}}{{sfn|Kraemer|2017|p=20}} Such chapels comprised one or more chambers for the bringing of offerings dedicated to the cult of the Ka of a deceased or of the king.{{sfn|Bolshakov|2001|p=217}} \nLike his father Teti, Pepi had such a chapel built in [[Bubastis]],{{sfn|Lange|2016|p=121}} in the Nile Delta region, \nas well as another one built in [[Nekhen|Hierakonpolis]],{{sfn|O'Connor|1992|pp=91\u201392|loc=fig. 5A}}{{sfn|Brovarski|1994|p=18}} in Upper Egypt and possibly also in [[Elkab]] where rock inscriptions refer to his funerary cult.{{sfn|Hendrickx|1999|p=344}} Further Ka chapels of Pepi have been found in Memphis, Zawyet el-Meytin, [[Assiut]] and [[Nagada]].{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|pp=16\u201317}} \nAll of these chapels were likely peripheral to large temples hosting extensive cult activities,{{sfn|O'Connor|1992|pp=84, 87, 96}} for example that at Bubastis was peripheral to the main Old Kingdom temple dedicated to the goddess [[Bastet]],{{sfn|Brovarski|1994|p=18}} while that at Abydos was likely next to the  temple of Khenti-Amentiu.{{sfn|Brovarski|1994|p=19}}\n\nBeneath the floor of Hierakonpolis chapel, in an underground store, [[James Quibell]] uncovered a statue of king [[Khasekhemwy]] of the [[Second Dynasty of Egypt|Second Dynasty]], a terracota lion cub made during the [[First Dynasty of Egypt|Thinite era]],{{sfn|Bongioanni|Croce|2001|p=84}} a golden mask representing [[Horus]] and two copper statues.{{sfn|Muhly|1999|p=630}} These statues, originally fashioned by hammering plates of copper over a wooden base{{sfn|Muhly|1999|p=630}}{{sfn|Peck|1999|p=875}} had been  disassembled and placed inside one another then sealed with a thin layer of engraved copper bearing the titles and names of Pepi I \"on the first day of the Heb Sed\" feast.{{sfn|Bongioanni|Croce|2001|p=84}} The two statues were symbolically \"trampling underfoot the [[Nine bows]]\"\u2014the ennemies of Egypt\u2014a stylized representation of Egypt's conquered foreign subjects.{{sfn|Grimal|1992|p=84}} While the identity of the larger adult figure as Pepi I is revealed by the inscription, the identity of the smaller statue showing a younger person remains unresolved.{{sfn|Bongioanni|Croce|2001|p=84}} The most common hypothesis among Egyptologists is that the young man shown is Merenre:{{sfn|Brovarski|1994|p=18}} \"who was publicly associated as his father's successor on the occasion of the Jubilee [the Heb Sed feast]. The placement of his copper effigy inside that of his father would therefore reflect the continuity of the royal succession and the passage of the royal sceptre from father to son before the death of the pharaoh could cause a dynastic split.\"{{sfn|Bongioanni|Croce|2001|pp=84\u201385}}\nAlternatively, Bongioanni and Croce have also proposed that the smaller statue may represent \"a more youthful Pepy I, reinvigorated by the celebration of the Jubilee ceremonies.\"{{sfn|Bongioanni|Croce|2001|p=85}}\n\nIn addition to building chapels, Pepi also decreed a tax-exemption for the Ka chapel of his mother located in [[Qift|Koptos]].{{efn|group=note|The decree recording this, called decree Coptos Decree (a) in modern Egyptology, is now in the Egyptian Museum Cairo, catalog number 41890.{{sfn|Hayes|1946|p=4}}}}{{sfn|Hayes|1946|p=4}} A similar decree has survived on a stela discovered near the [[Bent Pyramid]] in [[Dashur]], whereby in his 21st year of reign, Pepi grants exemptions to the people serving in the two pyramids of [[Sneferu]]:{{sfn|Edwards|1999|p=253}}\n{{cquote|text=My majesty has commanded that these two pyramid towns be exempt for him throughout the course of eternity from doing any work of the palace, from doing any forced labor for any part of the royal residence throughout the course of eternity, or from doing any forced labor at the word of anybody in the course of eternity.{{sfn|Redford|1992|p=61}}}}\n\nAt the southern border of Egypt, in [[Elephantine]], several [[faience]] plaques bearing Pepi's cartouche{{sfn|Dreyer|1986|loc=no. 428\u2013447}} have been uncovered in the temple of [[Satet]]. These\nwitness either to royal interest in the local cult{{sfn|Yurco|1999|p=240}} or to a royal attempt at affirming the king's stature in the provinces.{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|p=20}} An alabaster statue of an ape with its offspring bearing Pepi I's cartouche{{sfn|Dreyer|1986|loc=no. 455}} was also uncovered in the same location, but it was rather probably a gift of the king to a high official who then dedicated it to Satet.{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|p=17}} In this temple that Pepi built a red granite [[naos]]{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|p=17}} meant either to house the goddess\u2019s statue{{sfn|Kaiser|1999|p=337}} or a statue of Pepi I himself, making the naos into yet another Ka-chapel.{{sfn|Franke|1994|p=121}} The naos, which stands {{convert|1.32|m|ft|abbr=on}} high is inscribed with Pepi I's cartouche and the epithet \"beloved of Satet\".{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|p=17}} Pepi seems to have undertaken wider works in the temple, possibly reorganizing its layout by adding walls and an altar.{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|pp=17\u201318}} In this context, the faience tablets bearing his cartouche may be foundation offerings made at the start of the works,{{sfn|Dreyer|1986|p=94}} although this has been contested.{{sfn|Bussmann|2007|p=18}}\n\nFurther south, in Nubia, [[Weni the Elder]] oversaw the construction of a great canal at the First Cataract for the king.\n\n===Trade, mining and military activities===\n[[File:Ebla_-_DecArch_-_2-126.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Ebla's royal palace, destroyed c. 2300 BC]]\nMuch of the trade which had existed during the earlier Fifth Dynasty continued under Pepi I, with settlements along the [[Levant|Levantine coast]], in particular [[Byblos]], and indirectly from there{{sfn|Matthiae|1978|pp=230\u2013231}} with the city of [[Ebla]] in modern-day [[Syria]].{{sfn|M\u00e1lek|2000a|p=106}} The latter is established by alabaster vessels{{sfn|Redford|1992|p=41}} bearing Pepi's name found near Ebla's royal palace G,{{efn|group=note|For example, an alabaster lid of a precious vessel is inscribed with \"Beloved of the two lands, king of Upper and Lower Egypt, the son of Hathor, lady of Dendera, Pepi\". As Hathor was the chief deity of Byblos, it is likely that this vessel was destined to this city and was only later exchanged or given to Ebla.{{sfn|Matthiae|1978|pp=230\u2013232}}}}{{sfn|Matthiae|1978|pp=230\u2013231|loc=fig. 20}} destroyed in the 23rd century BC.{{sfn|Astour|2002|p=60}} At the same time, an extensive network of caravan routes traversed Egypt's [[Western Desert (Egypt)|Western Desert]], for example from Abydos to the [[Kharga Oasis]] and from there to the [[Dakhla Oasis|Dakhla]] and [[Selima Oasis|Selima]] Oases.{{sfn|M\u00e1lek|2000a|p=106}}\n\nExpedition and mining activities that were already taking place in the Fifth and early Sixth Dynasty continued unabated. These include at least one expedition to the mines of [[turquoise]] and [[copper]] in [[Wadi Maghareh]], [[Sinai Peninsula|Sinai]], {{sfn|M\u00e1lek|2000a|p=106}} circa Pepi's 36th year on the throne,{{sfn|Smith|1971|p=191}}\nan expedition to [[Hatnub]], where [[alabaster]] was extracted{{sfn|M\u00e1lek|2000a|p=106}} at least once on Pepi's 49th year of reign,{{sfn|Smith|1971|p=191}} as well as visits to the [[Gebel el-Silsila]]{{sfn|Smith|1999|p=394}} and [[Sehel Island]].{{sfn|Petrie|1897|p=89}} [[Greywacke]] and [[siltstone]] for building projects originated from quarries of the [[Wadi Hammamat]],{{sfn|M\u00e1lek|2000a|p=106}} where Pepi I is mentioned in circa eighty graffiti.{{sfn|Meyer|1999|p=1063}} \n\nMilitarily, Pepi I's reign was marked by aggressive expansion into [[Nubia]].{{sfn|Hayes|1978|p=122}} This is reported on the walls of the tombs of the contemporary nomarchs of Elephantine,{{sfn|Hayes|1978|p=122}} by alabaster vessels bearing Pepi's cartouche found in [[Kerma]]{{sfn|Smith|1971|p=194}} and by inscriptions in Tumas.{{sfn|Smith|1971|p=191}}\nTo the north-east of Egypt, Pepi launched at least five military expeditions against the \"sand dwellers\"{{efn|group=note|Transliteration from Ancient Egyptian ''\u1e25ryw-\u0161''.{{sfn|Goedicke|1963|p=188}}}} of Sinai and southern Palestine.{{sfn|Smith|1971|p=192}}{{sfn|Hayes|1978|p=125}} These campaigns are recounted on the walls of the tomb of Weni, then officially a palace superintendent but given the task of a general.{{sfn|Redford|1992|p=54}} Weni tells how he ordered nomarchs in Upper Egypt and the Nile Delta region to \"call up the levies of their own subordinates, and these in turn\nsummoned their subordinates down through every level of the local administration\".{{sfn|Schulman|1999|p=166}} Meanwhile, Nubian mercenaries were also recruited,{{sfn|Smith|1971|p=192}} so that in total tens of thousands of men were at Weni's disposal.{{sfn|Redford|1992|p=54}}\nThis is the only text relating the raising of an Egyptian army during the Old Kingdom period,{{sfn|Schulman|1999|p=166}} and it also indirectly reveals the absence of a permanent, standing army at the time.{{sfn|Kanawati|2003|p=1}}\nThe goal of this army was either to repulse and push-back rebelling [[Bedouin]]s{{sfn|Redford|1992|p=55}} and [[Semitic people]]{{efn|group=note|Transliteration from Ancient Egyptian ''3'mu'' often translated \"Semite\".{{sfn|Goedicke|1963|p=189}}}} or to seize their properties and conquer their land, possibly comprising parts of the Eastern Nile Delta.{{sfn|Goedicke|1963|pp=189\u2013197}} \nIn any case the Egyptians did invade Palestine up to what may be [[Mount Carmel]] in the north with the army, while also landing troops directly on the coast thanks to Egyptian transport boats.{{sfn|Smith|1971|p=192}}{{sfn|Hayes|1978|p=126}} Weni reports the destruction of walled towns, cutting down fig-trees and grape wines and setting fire to local shrines.{{sfn|Goedicke|1963|p=190}}\n\n==Chronology==\n=== Relative chronology ===\n[[File:Abydos KL 06-03 n36.jpg|thumb|upright|Pepi I's cartouche reading \"Meryre\" on the [[Abydos King List]]{{sfn|von Beckerath|1997|p=27}}]]\nThe relative chronology of Pepi I's reign is well established by historical records, contemporary artifacts and archeological evidences, which agree that he succeeded Userkare and was in turn succeeded by Merenre I Nemtyemsaf.{{sfn|von Beckerath|1999|pp=62\u201363|loc=king number 3}} For example, the near-contemporary [[South Saqqara Stone]], a royal annal inscribed during the reign of Pepi II, gives the succession \"Teti \u2192 Userkare \u2192 Pepi I \u2192 Merenre I\" for the early Sixth Dynasty. This is also the case of the [[Abydos king list]], written under [[Seti I]] and which gives Pepi I's cartouche on the 36th entry, between those of Userkare and Merenre.{{sfn|von Beckerath|1997|p=27}}\n\nAn historical source against this order of succession is the ''Aegyptiaca'' (\u0391\u1f30\u03b3\u03c5\u03c0\u03c4\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ac), a history of Egypt written in the 3rd century BC during the reign of [[Ptolemy II]] (283 \u2013 246 BC) by [[Manetho]]. No copies of the Aegyptiaca have survived and it is now known only through later writings by [[Sextus Julius Africanus]] and [[Eusebius]]. According to the Byzantine scholar [[George Syncellus]], Africanus wrote that the ''Aegyptiaca'' mentioned the succession \"Otho\u00eas \u2192 Phius \u2192 Methusuphis\" at the start of the Sixth Dynasty. Otho\u00eas, Phius (in [[Ancient Greek|Greek]], \u03c6\u03b9\u03cc\u03c2), and Methusuphis are believed to be the [[Hellenization|Hellenized]] forms for Teti, Pepi I and Merenre, respectively.{{sfn|Waddell|1971|p=53}} Manetho's reconstruction of the early Sixth Dynasty is in agreement with the [[Saqqara Tablet]], where Pepi's name is given on the 25th entry while Userkare is omitted.{{sfn|von Beckerath|1997|p=27}} This list was written under Ramses II.{{sfn|Daressy|1912|p=205}}\n\n===Length of Reign===\n[[Image:Offering vessel of Pepi I.jpg|thumb|left|150px|An offering vessel of Pepi I. It would have likely been used to celebrate this king's [[Heb Sed]] feast]]\nAn analysis of the [[South Saqqara Stone]] attests to a 25th [[cattle count]], its highest, during the reign of Pepi I. Evidence indicates that during the reigns of Pepi I and Merenre I Nemytemsaf the cattle count was conducted biennially, thus suggesting a regnal length of 49 years. However, a 50th year of reign cannot be discounted due to a missing fragment of the inscription following.{{sfn|Baud|Dobrev|1995|pp=46\u201349}} The [[Turin King List]] appears to list Pepi I with a reign of 20 years, while his successor Merenre I is accredited with a 44-year reign. This contradicts contemporaneous evidence from the stone whose highest attestation is the 5th cattle count. The Egyptologist [[Kim Ryholt]] suggests that the two entries might have been interchanged.{{sfn|Ryholt|1997|pp=13\u201314}}\n\nThere has been some doubt regarding whether the cattle count dating system was strictly biennial or slightly more irregular. That the latter situation appeared to be the case was suggested by the \"Year after the 18th Count, 3rd Month of Shemu day 27\" inscription from Wadi Hammamat No. 74-75 which mentions the \"first occurrence of the Heb Sed\" in that year for Pepi.<ref>Anthony Spalinger, Dated Texts of the Old Kingdom, SAK 21: 1994, p.303</ref> as well as a \"Year after the 18th Count, 4th Month of Shemu day 5\" date in Sinai graffito No. 106 as the French Egyptologist [[Michel Baud]] noted in a 2006 book on Egyptian chronology.{{sfn|Baud|2006|p=148}} This would be the year 36 if the biennial dating system was used. This information is significant because the [[Heb Sed|Heb Sed Feast]] was always celebrated in a king's Year 30. If Pepi I was using a biennial counting system during his reign, these ''heb sed'' inscriptions should have been dated to the Year after the 15th Count instead. This could imply that the cattle count during the 6th dynasty was not regularly biennial. Michel Baud, however, stresses that the Year of the 18th count is preserved in the [[South Saqqara Stone]] and writes that:\n[[File:Pepi I.jpg|thumb|right|160px|Ointment vase celebrating Pepi I's first ''Sed'' festival, [[Mus\u00e9e du Louvre]]. The inscription reads: ''The king of Upper and Lower Egypt Meryre, may he be given life for ever. The first occasion of the Sed festival''.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Nigel C.|last1= Strudwick|first2=Ronald J. |last2=Leprohon|title=Texts from the Pyramid Age|ISBN=9004130489|date=2005}}</ref>]]\n:\"Between the mention of count 18 [here] and the next memorial formula which belongs to count 19, end of register D, the available space for count 18+ is the expected half of the average size of a theoretical [year count] compartment. It is hard to believe that such a narrow space corresponds to the jubilee celebration, which obviously had a considerable importance for this (and every) king.\"{{sfn|Baud|2006|p=150}}\n\nBaud notes that there was a tendency during this ruler's administration to mention the first jubilee repeatedly in the years following its celebration\u2014in connection with intense building activity at the king's funerary complex until even to the end of Pepi I's reign when this pharaoh's highest date\u2014the Year of the 25th Count, 1st Month of [[Season of the Inundation|Akhet]] day [lost]--from Hatnub Inscription No.3.<ref>Spalinger, p.304</ref> appears; this ruler's final 25th count is also strikingly associated with Pepi I's first royal jubilee.{{sfn|Baud|2006|p=150}} The South Saqqara Stone confirms that Pepi I's last year was his Year of the 25th Count.\n\nTherefore, the references to Pepi I's first jubilee being celebrated in his 18th cattle count are likely just part of this royal tendency to emphasize the king's first jubilee years after it was first celebrated and Michel Baud (and F. Raffaele) both note that the longest year compartment in the South Saqqara Stone appears \"at the beginning of register D. Fortuituously or not, this [year] compartment corresponds perfectly to year 30/31, if a strictly biennial system of numbering is presumed\" for Pepi I's reign.{{sfn|Baud|2006|p=150}} (i.e. his 15th count) Therefore, the count was mostly likely biennial during Pepi I's reign and the reference to his final year\u2014the 25 count\u2014implies that he reigned for 49 full years.\n\n== Pyramid complex ==\n{{main|Pyramid of Pepi I}}\n[[File:2009 1027 165328AA Petrie Museum, London.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Fragments of the pyramid texts from Pepi I's pyramid in South Saqqara, now in the [[Petrie Museum]]]]\nPepi I had a pyramid built for himself in South Saqqara,{{sfn|Lehner|2008|p=157}} which he named ''Men-nefer-Pepi'' variously translated as \"Pepi's splendor is enduring\",{{sfn|Verner|2001d|p=351}} \"The perfection of Pepi is established\"{{sfn|Lehner|2008|p=158}} \"The beauty of Pepi endures\",{{sfn|Verner|2001b|p=590}}  and \"The perfection of Pepi endures\".{{sfn|Altenm\u00fcller|2001|p=603}} The diminutive name ''Mennefer'' for the pyramid complex gave rise to a novel designation for the nearby capital of Egypt originally called ''Ineb-hedj'', designation which ultimately gave [[Memphis, Egypt|Memphis]] in Greek.{{sfn|Verner|2001b|p=590}}{{sfn|Altenm\u00fcller|2001|p=603}}{{sfn|Grimal|1992|p=84}}\n\nPepi's main pyramid was constructed in the same fashion as others since [[Djedkare Isesi]]:{{sfn|Verner|2001d|p=352}} a core built six steps high from small roughly dressed blocks of limestone bound together using clay mortar encased with fine limestone blocks.{{sfn|Verner|2001d|pp= 325 & 352\u2013353}} The pyramid, now destroyed, had a base length of {{convert|78.75|m|ft+royal cubit|0|abbr=on}} converging to the apex at ~ 53\u00b0 and once stood {{convert|52.5|m|ft+royal cubit|0|abbr=on}} tall.{{sfn|Lehner|2008|p=158}} Its remains now form a mound a meagre {{convert|12|m|ft+royal cubit|0|abbr=on}},{{sfn|Verner|2001d|p=351}}{{sfn|Lehner|2008|p=157}} containing a pit in its centre dug by stone thieves.{{sfn|Lehner|2008|pp=157\u2013158}}\n\nThe substructure of the pyramid was accessed from the north chapel which has since disappeared. From the entrance, a descending corridor gives way to a vestibule leading into the horizontal passage. Halfway along the passage three granite portcullises guard the chambers. As in preceding pyramids, the substructure contains three chambers: an antechamber on the pyramids vertical axis, a ''serdab'' with three recesses to its east, and a burial chamber containing the king's sarcophagus to the west.{{sfn|Verner|2001d|pp=353\u2013354}} Extraordinarily, the pink granite canopic chest that is sunk into the floor at the foot of the sarcophagus has remained undisturbed.{{sfn|Lehner|2008|p=158}}{{sfn|Hellum|2007|p=107}} Discovered alongside it was a bundle of viscera presumed to belong to the pharaoh.{{sfn|Hellum|2007|p=107}} The provenance of a mummy fragment and fine linen wrappings discovered in the burial chamber are unknown, but are hypothesized to belong to Pepi I.{{sfn|Verner|2001d|p=354}}\n\nThe walls of Pepi I's antechamber, burial chamber, and much of the corridor{{efn|The corridor texts in Pepi I's pyramid are the most extensive, covering the whole horizontal passage, the vestibule, and even a section of the descending corridor.{{sfn|Allen|2005|p=12}}{{sfn|Hays|2012|p=111}} Unas' pyramid constrained the texts to the south section of the corridor,{{sfn|Lehner|2008|p=154}} as did Teti's.{{sfn|Allen|2005|p=12}} The texts in Merenre I's and Pepi II's pyramids covered the entire corridor and the vestibule.{{sfn|Allen|2005|p=12}}}} are covered in vertical columns of inscribed hieroglyphic text,{{sfn|Hayes|1978|p=82}}{{sfn|Verner|2001d|p=354}}{{sfn|Lehner|2008|p=158}} painted green with ground [[malachite]] and [[gum arabic]], a color symbolizing renewal.{{sfn|Leclant|1999|p=867}}\nHis sarcophagus is also inscribed on its east side with the king's titles and names, as part of a larger set of spells that includes texts at the bottom of the north and south walls opposite the sarcophagus, and in a line running across the top of the north, west, and south walls of the chamber.{{sfn|Allen|2005|p=97 & 100}} The writing comprises 2,263 columns and lines of text, making them the most extensive corpus of Pyramid Texts from the Old Kingdom.{{sfn|Allen|2005|p=97}} The tradition of inscribing texts inside the pyramid was begun by Unas at the end of the Fifth Dynasty,{{sfn|M\u00e1lek|2000a|p=102}}{{sfn|Allen|2001|p=95}}{{sfn|Verner|2001b|p=590}} but originally discovered in Pepi I's pyramid in 1880.{{sfn|Verner|2001d|pp=39\u201340}}{{sfn|Lehner|2008|p=158}} Their function, in congruence with all [[Ancient Egyptian funerary texts|funerary literature]], was to enable the reunion of the ruler's ''ba'' and ''ka'' leading to the transformation into an ''akh'',{{sfn|Allen|2005|pp=7\u20138}}{{sfn|Lehner|2008|p=24}} and to secure eternal life among the gods in the sky.{{sfn|Verner|1994|p=57}}{{sfn|Grimal|1992|p=126}}{{sfn|Hays|2012|p=10}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|group=note}}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Pepi I}}\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n:{{cite book|last=Allen|first=James|author-link=James Peter Allen|chapter=Pyramid Texts|editor-last=Redford|editor-first=Donald B.|editor-link=Donald B. Redford|year=2001|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Ancient Egypt, Volume 3|location=Oxford|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-510234-5|pp=95\u201398|ref=harv}}\n:{{cite book|last1=Allen|first1=James|editor-last=Der Manuelian|editor-first=Peter|year=2005|title=The Ancient Egyptian Pyramid Texts|publisher=Society of Biblical Literature|location=Atlanta|series=Writings from the Ancient World, Number 23|isbn=978-1-58983-182-7|ref=harv}}\n:{{cite book|last=Altenm\u00fcller|first=Hartwig|author-link=Hartwig Altenm\u00fcller|chapter=Old Kingdom: Fifth Dynasty|editor-last=Redford|editor-first=Donald B.|editor-link=Donald B. Redford|year=2001|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Ancient Egypt, Volume 2|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-510234-5|pp=597\u2013601|ref=harv}}\n:{{cite book|last=Astour|first=Michael C.|chapter=A Reconstruction of the History of Ebla (Part 2)|title=Eblaitica: Essays on the Ebla Archives and Eblaite Language|editor1-first=Cyrus H.|editor1-last=Gordon|editor2-first=Gary A.|